# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: group-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] In mathematics, an **abelian group**,[note 1] also called a **commutative group**, is a group in which the result of applying the group operation to two group elements does not depend on the order in which they are written.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] That is, the group operation is commutative.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] With addition as an operation, the integers and the real numbers form abelian groups, and the concept of an abelian group may be viewed as a generalization of these examples.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Abelian groups are named after the Norwegian mathematician Niels Henrik Abel.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The concept of an abelian group underlies many fundamental algebraic structures, such as fields, rings, vector spaces, and algebras.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The theory of abelian groups is generally simpler than that of their non-abelian counterparts, and finite abelian groups are very well understood and fully classified.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] An abelian group is a set A , together with an operation ･ , that combines any two elements a and b of A to form another element of $A,$ denoted $a\cdot b$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The symbol ･ is a general placeholder for a concretely given operation.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Some authors further include as requirements some properties that belong to the definition of an operation: that the operation is *defined* for any ordered pair of elements of A, that the result is *well-defined*, and that the result *belongs to* A.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] A group in which the group operation is not commutative is called a *non-abelian group* or *non-commutative group*.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] There are two main notational conventions for abelian groups – additive and multiplicative.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Generally, the multiplicative notation is the usual notation for groups, while the additive notation is the usual notation for modules and rings.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The additive notation may also be used to emphasize that a particular group is abelian, whenever both abelian and non-abelian groups are considered, with some notable exceptions being near-rings and partially ordered groups, where an operation is written additively even when non-abelian.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] To verify that a finite group is abelian, a table (matrix) – known as a Cayley table – can be constructed in a similar fashion to a multiplication table.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] If the group is $G=\{g_{1}=e,g_{2},\dots ,g_{n}\}$ under the operation $\cdot$ , the $(i,j)$ -th entry of this table contains the product $g_{i}\cdot g_{j}$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The group is abelian if and only if this table is symmetric about the main diagonal, which means that for all $i,j=1,...,n$ , the $(i,j)$ entry of the table equals the $(j,i)$ entry.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] In general, matrices, even invertible matrices, do not form an abelian group under multiplication because matrix multiplication is generally not commutative.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] However, some groups of matrices are abelian groups under matrix multiplication – one example is the group of $2\times 2$ rotation matrices.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Camille Jordan named abelian groups after the Norwegian mathematician Niels Henrik Abel, who had found that the commutativity of the group of a polynomial implies that the roots of the polynomial can be calculated by using radicals.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] If n is a natural number and x is an element of an abelian group G written additively, then $nx$ can be defined as $x+x+\cdots +x$ ( n summands) and $(-n)x=-(nx)$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] In this way, G becomes a module over the ring $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] In fact, the modules over $\mathbb {Z}$ can be identified with the abelian groups.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Theorems about abelian groups (i.e. modules over the principal ideal domain $\mathbb {Z}$ ) can often be generalized to theorems about modules over an arbitrary principal ideal domain.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] A typical example is the classification of finitely generated abelian groups which is a specialization of the structure theorem for finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] In the case of finitely generated abelian groups, this theorem guarantees that an abelian group splits as a direct sum of a torsion group and a free abelian group.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The former may be written as a direct sum of finitely many groups of the form $\mathbb {Z} /p^{k}\mathbb {Z}$ for p prime, and the latter is a direct sum of finitely many copies of $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] If $f,g:G\to H$ are two group homomorphisms between abelian groups, then their sum $f+g$ , defined by $(f+g)(x)=f(x)+g(x)$ , is again a homomorphism.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] (This is not true if H is a non-abelian group.) The set ${\text{Hom}}(G,H)$ of all group homomorphisms from G to H is therefore an abelian group in its own right.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Somewhat akin to the dimension of vector spaces, every abelian group has a *rank*.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] It is defined as the maximal cardinality of a set of linearly independent (over the integers) elements of the group.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Finite abelian groups and torsion groups have rank zero, and every abelian group of rank zero is a torsion group.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The integers and the rational numbers have rank one, as well as every nonzero additive subgroup of the rationals.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] On the other hand, the multiplicative group of the nonzero rationals has an infinite rank, as it is a free abelian group with the set of the prime numbers as a basis (this results from the fundamental theorem of arithmetic).
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The center $Z(G)$ of a group G is the set of elements that commute with every element of G .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] A group G is abelian if and only if it is equal to its center $Z(G)$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The center of a group G is always a characteristic abelian subgroup of G .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] If the quotient group $G/Z(G)$ of a group by its center is cyclic then G is abelian.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Cyclic groups of integers modulo n , $\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z}$ , were among the first examples of groups.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] It turns out that an arbitrary finite abelian group is isomorphic to a direct sum of finite cyclic groups of prime power order, and these orders are uniquely determined, forming a complete system of invariants.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The automorphism group of a finite abelian group can be described directly in terms of these invariants.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The theory had been first developed in the 1879 paper of Georg Frobenius and Ludwig Stickelberger and later was both simplified and generalized to finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain, forming an important chapter of linear algebra.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Any group of prime order is isomorphic to a cyclic group and therefore abelian.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Any group whose order is a square of a prime number is also abelian.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] In fact, for every prime number p there are (up to isomorphism) exactly two groups of order $p^{2}$ , namely $\mathbb {Z} _{p^{2}}$ and $\mathbb {Z} _{p}\times \mathbb {Z} _{p}$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The **fundamental theorem of finite abelian groups** states that every finite abelian group G can be expressed as the direct sum of cyclic subgroups of prime-power order; it is also known as the **basis theorem for finite abelian groups**.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Moreover, automorphism groups of cyclic groups are examples of abelian groups.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] This is generalized by the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups, with finite groups being the special case when *G* has zero rank; this in turn admits numerous further generalizations.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The classification was proven by Leopold Kronecker in 1870, though it was not stated in modern group-theoretic terms until later, and was preceded by a similar classification of quadratic forms by Carl Friedrich Gauss in 1801; see history for details.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The cyclic group $\mathbb {Z} _{mn}$ of order $mn$ is isomorphic to the direct sum of $\mathbb {Z} _{m}$ and $\mathbb {Z} _{n}$ if and only if m and n are coprime.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The same can be said for any abelian group of order 15, leading to the remarkable conclusion that all abelian groups of order 15 are isomorphic.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] See also list of small groups for finite abelian groups of order 30 or less.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] One can apply the fundamental theorem to count (and sometimes determine) the automorphisms of a given finite abelian group G .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Given this, the fundamental theorem shows that to compute the automorphism group of G it suffices to compute the automorphism groups of the Sylow p -subgroups separately (that is, all direct sums of cyclic subgroups, each with order a power of p ).
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] One special case is when $n=1$ , so that there is only one cyclic prime-power factor in the Sylow p -subgroup P .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] In this case the theory of automorphisms of a finite cyclic group can be used.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Another special case is when n is arbitrary but $e_{i}=1$ for $1\leq i\leq n$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] so elements of this subgroup can be viewed as comprising a vector space of dimension n over the finite field of p elements $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] where $\mathrm {GL}$ is the appropriate general linear group.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] In the most general case, where the $e_{i}$ and n are arbitrary, the automorphism group is more difficult to determine.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] One can check that this yields the orders in the previous examples as special cases (see Hillar & Rhea).
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] An abelian group A is finitely generated if it contains a finite set of elements (called *generators*) $G=\{x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}\}$ such that every element of the group is a linear combination with integer coefficients of elements of G.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] This homomorphism is surjective, and its kernel is finitely generated (since integers form a Noetherian ring).
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Consider the matrix M with integer entries, such that the entries of its jth column are the coefficients of the jth generator of the kernel.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Then, the abelian group is isomorphic to the cokernel of linear map defined by M.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Conversely every integer matrix defines a finitely generated abelian group.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] It follows that the study of finitely generated abelian groups is totally equivalent with the study of integer matrices.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] In particular, changing the generating set of A is equivalent with multiplying M on the left by a unimodular matrix (that is, an invertible integer matrix whose inverse is also an integer matrix).
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Changing the generating set of the kernel of M is equivalent with multiplying M on the right by a unimodular matrix.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] where U and V are unimodular, and S is a matrix such that all non-diagonal entries are zero, the non-zero diagonal entries ⁠ $d_{1,1},\ldots ,d_{k,k}$ ⁠ are the first ones, and ⁠ $d_{j,j}$ ⁠ is a divisor of ⁠ $d_{i,i}$ ⁠ for *i* > *j*.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] where r is the number of zero rows at the bottom of S (and also the rank of the group).
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] This is the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The existence of algorithms for Smith normal form shows that the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups is not only a theorem of abstract existence, but provides a way for computing expression of finitely generated abelian groups as direct sums.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The simplest infinite abelian group is the infinite cyclic group $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Any finitely generated abelian group A is isomorphic to the direct sum of r copies of $\mathbb {Z}$ and a finite abelian group, which in turn is decomposable into a direct sum of finitely many cyclic groups of prime power orders.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Even though the decomposition is not unique, the number r , called the rank of A , and the prime powers giving the orders of finite cyclic summands are uniquely determined.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] By contrast, classification of general infinitely generated abelian groups is far from complete.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Divisible groups, i.e. abelian groups A in which the equation $nx=a$ admits a solution $x\in A$ for any natural number n and element a of A , constitute one important class of infinite abelian groups that can be completely characterized.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Every divisible group is isomorphic to a direct sum, with summands isomorphic to $\mathbb {Q}$ and Prüfer groups $\mathbb {Q} _{p}/\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ for various prime numbers p , and the cardinality of the set of summands of each type is uniquely determined.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Moreover, if a divisible group A is a subgroup of an abelian group G then A admits a direct complement: a subgroup C of G such that $G=A\oplus C$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Thus divisible groups are injective modules in the category of abelian groups, and conversely, every injective abelian group is divisible (Baer's criterion).
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] An abelian group without non-zero divisible subgroups is called **reduced**.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Two important special classes of infinite abelian groups with diametrically opposite properties are *torsion groups* and *torsion-free groups*, exemplified by the groups $\mathbb {Q} /\mathbb {Z}$ (periodic) and $\mathbb {Q}$ (torsion-free).
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] An abelian group is called **periodic** or **torsion**, if every element has finite order.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] A direct sum of finite cyclic groups is periodic.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Although the converse statement is not true in general, some special cases are known.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The first and second Prüfer theorems state that if A is a periodic group, and it either has a **bounded exponent**, i.e., $nA=0$ for some natural number n , or is countable and the p -heights of the elements of A are finite for each p , then A is isomorphic to a direct sum of finite cyclic groups.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The cardinality of the set of direct summands isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z} /p^{m}\mathbb {Z}$ in such a decomposition is an invariant of A .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] These theorems were later subsumed in the **Kulikov criterion**.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] In a different direction, Helmut Ulm found an extension of the second Prüfer theorem to countable abelian p -groups with elements of infinite height: those groups are completely classified by means of their Ulm invariants.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] An abelian group is called **torsion-free** if every non-zero element has infinite order.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] An abelian group that is neither periodic nor torsion-free is called **mixed**.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] If A is an abelian group and $T(A)$ is its torsion subgroup, then the factor group $A/T(A)$ is torsion-free.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] However, in general the torsion subgroup is not a direct summand of A , so A is *not* isomorphic to $T(A)\oplus A/T(A)$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Thus the theory of mixed groups involves more than simply combining the results about periodic and torsion-free groups.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The additive group $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers is torsion-free $\mathbb {Z}$ -module.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] One of the most basic invariants of an infinite abelian group A is its rank: the cardinality of the maximal linearly independent subset of A .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Abelian groups of rank 0 are precisely the periodic groups, while torsion-free abelian groups of rank 1 are necessarily subgroups of $\mathbb {Q}$ and can be completely described.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] More generally, a torsion-free abelian group of finite rank r is a subgroup of $\mathbb {Q} _{r}$ .
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] On the other hand, the group of p -adic integers $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ is a torsion-free abelian group of infinite $\mathbb {Z}$ -rank and the groups $\mathbb {Z} _{p}^{n}$ with different n are non-isomorphic, so this invariant does not even fully capture properties of some familiar groups.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The classification theorems for finitely generated, divisible, countable periodic, and rank 1 torsion-free abelian groups explained above were all obtained before 1950 and form a foundation of the classification of more general infinite abelian groups.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Important technical tools used in classification of infinite abelian groups are pure and basic subgroups.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Introduction of various invariants of torsion-free abelian groups has been one avenue of further progress.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] See the books by Irving Kaplansky, László Fuchs, Phillip Griffith, and David Arnold, as well as the proceedings of the conferences on Abelian Group Theory published in *Lecture Notes in Mathematics* for more recent findings.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The additive group of a ring is an abelian group, but not all abelian groups are additive groups of rings (with nontrivial multiplication).
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Many large abelian groups possess a natural topology, which turns them into topological groups.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] The collection of all abelian groups, together with the homomorphisms between them, forms the category ${\textbf {Ab}}$ , the prototype of an abelian category.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Wanda Szmielew (1955) proved that the first-order theory of abelian groups, unlike its non-abelian counterpart, is decidable.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Most algebraic structures other than Boolean algebras are undecidable.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Moreover, abelian groups of infinite order lead, quite surprisingly, to deep questions about the set theory commonly assumed to underlie all of mathematics.
[src:group-theory/abelian-group] Take the Whitehead problem: are all Whitehead groups of infinite order also free abelian groups?
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] In abstract algebra, a **cyclic group** or **monogenous group** is a group, denoted C*n* (also frequently **$\mathbb {Z}$***n* or Z*n*, not to be confused with the commutative ring of p-adic numbers), that is generated by a single element.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] That is, it is a set of invertible elements with a single associative binary operation, and it contains an element *g* such that every other element of the group may be obtained by repeatedly applying the group operation to *g* or its inverse.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Each element can be written as an integer power of *g* in multiplicative notation, or as an integer multiple of *g* in additive notation.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] This element *g* is called a *generator* of the group.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Every infinite cyclic group is isomorphic to the additive group of **Z**, the integers.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Every finite cyclic group of order *n* is isomorphic to the additive group of **Z**/*n***Z**, the integers modulo *n*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Every cyclic group is an abelian group (meaning that its group operation is commutative), and every finitely generated abelian group is a direct product of cyclic groups.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Every cyclic group of prime order is a simple group, which cannot be broken down into smaller groups.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] In the classification of finite simple groups, one of the three infinite classes consists of the cyclic groups of prime order.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The cyclic groups of prime order are thus among the building blocks from which all groups can be built.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For any element *g* in any group *G*, one can form the subgroup that consists of all its integer powers: ⟨*g*⟩ = { *g**k* | *k* ∈ **Z** }, called the **cyclic subgroup** generated by *g*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The order of *g* is |⟨*g*⟩|, the number of elements in ⟨*g*⟩, conventionally abbreviated as |*g*|, as ord(*g*), or as o(*g*).
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] That is, the order of an element is equal to the order of the cyclic subgroup that it generates.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A *cyclic group* is a group which is equal to one of its cyclic subgroups: *G* = ⟨*g*⟩ for some element *g*, called a *generator* of *G*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] An abstract group defined by this multiplication is often denoted C*n*, and we say that *G* is isomorphic to the standard cyclic group C*n*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Such a group is also isomorphic to **Z**/*n***Z**, the group of integers modulo *n* with the addition operation, which is the standard cyclic group in additive notation.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Under the isomorphism *χ* defined by *χ*(*g**i*) = *i* the identity element *e* corresponds to 0, products correspond to sums, and powers correspond to multiples.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Under a change of letters, this is isomorphic to (structurally the same as) the standard cyclic group of order 6, defined as C6 = ⟨*g*⟩ = { *e*, *g*, *g*2, *g*3, *g*4, *g*5 } with multiplication *g**j* · *g**k* = *g**j*+*k* (mod 6), so that *g*6 = *g*0 = *e*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] These groups are also isomorphic to **Z**/6**Z** = {0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5} with the operation of addition modulo 6, with *z**k* and *g**k* corresponding to *k*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Instead of the quotient notations **Z**/*n***Z**, **Z**/(*n*), or **Z**/*n*, some authors denote a finite cyclic group as **Z***n*, but this clashes with the notation of number theory, where **Z***p* denotes a *p*-adic number ring, or localization at a prime ideal.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] On the other hand, in an **infinite cyclic group** *G* = ⟨*g*⟩, the powers *g**k* give distinct elements for all integers *k*, so that *G* = { ... , *g*−2, *g*−1, *e*, *g*, *g*2, ... }, and *G* is isomorphic to the standard group C = C∞ and to **Z**, the additive group of the integers.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Here there are no finite cycles, and the name "cyclic" may be misleading.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] To avoid this confusion, Bourbaki introduced the term **monogenous group** for a group with a single generator and restricted "cyclic group" to mean a finite monogenous group, avoiding the term "infinite cyclic group".
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The set of integers **Z**, with the operation of addition, forms a group.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] It is an **infinite cyclic group**, because all integers can be written by repeatedly adding or subtracting the single number 1.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] In this group, 1 and −1 are the only generators.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Every infinite cyclic group is isomorphic to **Z**.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For every positive integer *n*, the set of integers modulo *n*, again with the operation of addition, forms a finite cyclic group, denoted **Z**/*n***Z**.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A modular integer *i* is a generator of this group if *i* is relatively prime to *n*, because these elements can generate all other elements of the group through integer addition.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] (The number of such generators is *φ*(*n*), where *φ* is the Euler totient function.) Every finite cyclic group *G* is isomorphic to **Z**/*n***Z**, where *n* = |*G*| is the order of the group.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The addition operations on integers and modular integers, used to define the cyclic groups, are the addition operations of commutative rings, also denoted **Z** and **Z**/*n***Z** or **Z**/(*n*).
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] If *p* is a prime, then **Z**/*p**Z*** is a finite field, and is usually denoted **F***p* or GF(*p*) for Galois field.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For every positive integer *n*, the set of the integers modulo *n* that are relatively prime to *n* is written as (**Z**/*n***Z**)×; it forms a group under the operation of multiplication.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] This group is not always cyclic, but is so whenever *n* is 1, 2, 4, a power of an odd prime, or twice a power of an odd prime (sequence A033948 in the OEIS).
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] This is the multiplicative group of units of the ring **Z**/*n***Z**; there are *φ*(*n*) of them, where again *φ* is the Euler totient function.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For example, (**Z**/6**Z**)× = {1, 5}, and since 6 is twice an odd prime this is a cyclic group.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] When (**Z**/*n***Z**)× is cyclic, its generators are called primitive roots modulo *n*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For a prime number *p*, the group (**Z**/*p***Z**)× is always cyclic, consisting of the non-zero elements of the finite field of order *p*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] More generally, every finite subgroup of the multiplicative group of any field is cyclic.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The set of rotational symmetries of a polygon forms a finite cyclic group.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] If there are *n* different ways of moving the polygon to itself by a rotation (including the null rotation) then this symmetry group is isomorphic to **Z**/*n***Z**.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] In three or higher dimensions there exist other finite symmetry groups that are cyclic, but which are not all rotations around an axis, but instead rotoreflections.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The group of all rotations of a circle (the circle group, also denoted *S*1) is *not* cyclic, because there is no single rotation whose integer powers generate all rotations.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] In fact, the infinite cyclic group C∞ is countable, while *S*1 is not.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The group of rotations by rational angles *is* countable, but still not cyclic.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] An *n*th root of unity is a complex number whose *n*th power is 1, a root of the polynomial *x**n* − 1.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The set of all *n*th roots of unity forms a cyclic group of order *n* under multiplication.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The generators of this cyclic group are the *n*th primitive roots of unity; they are the roots of the *n*th cyclotomic polynomial.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The Galois group of the field extension of the rational numbers generated by the *n*th roots of unity forms a different group, isomorphic to the multiplicative group (**Z/***n***Z**)× of order *φ*(*n*), which is cyclic for some but not all *n* (see above).
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A field extension is called a cyclic extension if its Galois group is cyclic.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For fields of characteristic zero, such extensions are the subject of Kummer theory, and are intimately related to solvability by radicals.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For an extension of finite fields of characteristic *p*, its Galois group is always finite and cyclic, generated by a power of the Frobenius mapping.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Conversely, given a finite field *F* and a finite cyclic group *G*, there is a finite field extension of *F* whose Galois group is *G*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] All subgroups and quotient groups of cyclic groups are cyclic.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Specifically, all subgroups of **Z** are of the form ⟨*m*⟩ = *m***Z**, with *m* a positive integer.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] All of these subgroups are distinct from each other, and apart from the trivial group {0} = 0**Z**, they all are isomorphic to **Z**.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The lattice of subgroups of **Z** is isomorphic to the dual of the lattice of natural numbers ordered by divisibility.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Thus, since a prime number *p* has no nontrivial divisors, *p***Z** is a maximal proper subgroup, and the quotient group **Z**/*p***Z** is simple; in fact, a cyclic group is simple if and only if its order is prime.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For every positive divisor *d* of *n*, the quotient group **Z**/*n***Z** has precisely one subgroup of order *d*, generated by the residue class of *n*/*d*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] That is, its group operation is commutative: *gh* = *hg* (for all *g* and *h* in *G*).
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] This is clear for the groups of integer and modular addition since *r* + *s* ≡ *s* + *r* (mod *n*), and it follows for all cyclic groups since they are all isomorphic to these standard groups.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For a finite cyclic group of order *n*, *g**n* is the identity element for any element *g*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] This again follows by using the isomorphism to modular addition, since *kn* ≡ 0 (mod *n*) for every integer *k*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For a prime power $p^{k}$ , the group $Z/p^{k}Z$ is called a primary cyclic group.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The fundamental theorem of abelian groups states that every finitely generated abelian group is a finite direct product of primary cyclic and infinite cyclic groups.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Because a cyclic group is abelian, each of its conjugacy classes consists of a single element.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A cyclic group of order *n* therefore has *n* conjugacy classes.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] If *d* is a divisor of *n*, then the number of elements in **Z**/*n***Z** which have order *d* is *φ*(*d*), and the number of elements whose order divides *d* is exactly *d*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] If *G* is a finite group in which, for each *n* > 0, *G* contains at most *n* elements of order dividing *n*, then *G* must be cyclic.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] If *n* and *m* are coprime, then the direct product of two cyclic groups **Z**/*n***Z** and **Z**/*m***Z** is isomorphic to the cyclic group **Z**/*nm***Z**, and the converse also holds: this is one form of the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] If *p* is a prime number, then any group with *p* elements is isomorphic to the simple group **Z**/*p***Z**.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A number *n* is called a cyclic number if **Z**/*n***Z** is the only group of order *n*, which is true exactly when gcd(*n*, *φ*(*n*)) = 1.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The sequence of cyclic numbers include all primes, but some are composite such as 15.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] However, all cyclic numbers are odd except 2.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The definition immediately implies that cyclic groups have group presentation C∞ = ⟨*x* | ⟩ and C*n* = ⟨*x* | *x**n*⟩ for finite *n*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The representation theory of the cyclic group is a critical base case for the representation theory of more general finite groups.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] In the complex case, a representation of a cyclic group decomposes into a direct sum of linear characters, making the connection between character theory and representation theory transparent.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] In the positive characteristic case, the indecomposable representations of the cyclic group form a model and inductive basis for the representation theory of groups with cyclic Sylow subgroups and more generally the representation theory of blocks of cyclic defect.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A **cycle graph** illustrates the various cycles of a group and is particularly useful in visualizing the structure of small finite groups.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A cycle graph for a cyclic group is simply a circular graph, where the group order is equal to the number of nodes.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A single generator defines the group as a directional path on the graph, and the inverse generator defines a backwards path.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A trivial path (identity) can be drawn as a loop but is usually suppressed.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Z2 is sometimes drawn with two curved edges as a multigraph.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A cyclic group Z*n*, with order *n*, corresponds to a single cycle graphed simply as an *n*-sided polygon with the elements at the vertices.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A Cayley graph is a graph defined from a pair (*G*,*S*) where *G* is a group and *S* is a set of generators for the group; it has a vertex for each group element, and an edge for each product of an element with a generator.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] In the case of a finite cyclic group, with its single generator, the Cayley graph is a cycle graph, and for an infinite cyclic group with its generator the Cayley graph is a doubly infinite path graph.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] However, Cayley graphs can be defined from other sets of generators as well.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The Cayley graphs of cyclic groups with arbitrary generator sets are called circulant graphs.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] These graphs may be represented geometrically as a set of equally spaced points on a circle or on a line, with each point connected to neighbors with the same set of distances as each other point.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] They are exactly the vertex-transitive graphs whose symmetry group includes a transitive cyclic group.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The endomorphism ring of the abelian group **Z**/*n***Z** is isomorphic to **Z**/*n***Z** itself as a ring.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Under this isomorphism, the number *r* corresponds to the endomorphism of **Z**/*n***Z** that maps each element to the sum of *r* copies of it.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] This is a bijection if and only if *r* is coprime with *n*, so the automorphism group of **Z**/*n***Z** is isomorphic to the unit group (**Z**/*n***Z**)×.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Similarly, the endomorphism ring of the additive group of **Z** is isomorphic to the ring **Z**.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Its automorphism group is isomorphic to the group of units of the ring **Z**, which is ({−1, +1}, ×) ≅ C2.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For the tensor product, this is a consequence of the general fact that *R*/*I* ⊗*R* *R*/*J* ≅ *R*/(*I* + *J*), where *R* is a commutative ring with unit and *I* and *J* are ideals of the ring.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] For the Hom group, recall that it is isomorphic to the subgroup of **Z** / *n***Z** consisting of the elements of order dividing *m*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] That subgroup is cyclic of order gcd(*m*, *n*), which completes the proof.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A group is called **virtually cyclic** if it contains a cyclic subgroup of finite index (the number of cosets that the subgroup has).
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] In other words, any element in a virtually cyclic group can be arrived at by multiplying a member of the cyclic subgroup and a member of a certain finite set.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Every cyclic group is virtually cyclic, as is every finite group.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] An infinite group is virtually cyclic if and only if it is finitely generated and has exactly two ends; an example of such a group is the direct product of **Z**/*n***Z** and **Z**, in which the factor **Z** has finite index *n*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Every abelian subgroup of a Gromov hyperbolic group is virtually cyclic.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A profinite group is called **procyclic** if it can be topologically generated by a single element.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Examples of profinite groups include the profinite integers ${\widehat {\mathbb {Z} }}$ or the *p*-adic integers $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ for a prime number *p*.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A locally cyclic group is a group in which each finitely generated subgroup is cyclic.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] An example is the additive group of the rational numbers: every finite set of rational numbers is a set of integer multiples of a single unit fraction, the inverse of their lowest common denominator, and generates as a subgroup a cyclic group of integer multiples of this unit fraction.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A group is locally cyclic if and only if its lattice of subgroups is a distributive lattice.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A cyclically ordered group is a group together with a cyclic order preserved by the group structure.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Every cyclic group can be given a structure as a cyclically ordered group, consistent with the ordering of the integers (or the integers modulo the order of the group).
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Every finite subgroup of a cyclically ordered group is cyclic.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A metacyclic group is a group containing a cyclic normal subgroup whose quotient is also cyclic.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] These groups include the cyclic groups, the dicyclic groups, and the direct products of two cyclic groups.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] The polycyclic groups generalize metacyclic groups by allowing more than one level of group extension.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] A group is polycyclic if it has a finite descending sequence of subgroups, each of which is normal in the previous subgroup with a cyclic quotient, ending in the trivial group.
[src:group-theory/cyclic-group] Every finitely generated abelian group or nilpotent group is polycyclic.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Many sets of transformations form a group under function composition; for example, the rotations around a point in the plane.
[src:group-theory/group-action] It is often useful to consider the group as an abstract group, and to say that one has a group action of the abstract group that consists of performing the transformations of the group of transformations.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The reason for distinguishing the group from the transformations is that, generally, a group of transformations of a structure acts also on various related structures; for example, the above rotation group also acts on triangles by transforming triangles into triangles.
[src:group-theory/group-action] If a group acts on a structure, it will usually also act on objects built from that structure.
[src:group-theory/group-action] For example, the group of Euclidean isometries acts on Euclidean space and also on the figures drawn in it; in particular, it acts on the set of all triangles.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Similarly, the group of symmetries of a polyhedron acts on the vertices, the edges, and the faces of the polyhedron.
[src:group-theory/group-action] A group action on a vector space is called a representation of the group.
[src:group-theory/group-action] In the case of a finite-dimensional vector space, it allows one to identify many groups with subgroups of the general linear group $\operatorname {GL} (n,K)$ , the group of the invertible matrices of dimension n over a field K .
[src:group-theory/group-action] The symmetric group $S_{n}$ acts on any set with n elements by permuting the elements of the set.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Although the group of all permutations of a set depends formally on the set, the concept of group action allows one to consider a single group for studying the permutations of all sets with the same cardinality.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The group G is then said to act on X (from the left).
[src:group-theory/group-action] A set X together with an action of G is called a (*left*) G -*set*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] It can be notationally convenient to curry the action $\alpha$ , so that, instead, one has a collection of transformations $\alpha _{g}:X\rightarrow X$ , with one transformation $\alpha _{g}$ for each group element $g\in G$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] The identity and compatibility relations then read $\alpha _{e}(x)=x$ and $\alpha _{g}(\alpha _{h}(x))=(\alpha _{g}\circ \alpha _{h})(x)=\alpha _{gh}(x)$ The second axiom states that the function composition is compatible with the group multiplication; they form a commutative diagram.
[src:group-theory/group-action] This axiom can be shortened even further, and written as $\alpha _{g}\circ \alpha _{h}=\alpha _{gh}$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] With the above understanding, it is very common to avoid writing $\alpha$ entirely, and to replace it with either a dot, or with nothing at all.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Thus, $\alpha (g,x)$ can be shortened to $g\cdot x$ or $gx$ , especially when the action is clear from context.
[src:group-theory/group-action] From these two axioms, it follows that for any fixed g in G , the function from X to itself which maps x to $g\cdot x$ is a bijection, with inverse bijection the corresponding map for $g^{-1}$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] Therefore, one may equivalently define a group action of G on X as a group homomorphism from G into the symmetric group $\operatorname {Sym} (X)$ of all bijections from X to itself.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The difference between left and right actions is in the order in which a product $gh$ acts on x .
[src:group-theory/group-action] For a left action, h acts first, followed by g second.
[src:group-theory/group-action] For a right action, g acts first, followed by h second.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Because of the formula $(gh)^{-1}=h^{-1}g^{-1}$ , a left action can be constructed from a right action by composing with the inverse operation of the group.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Also, a right action of a group G on X can be considered as a left action of its opposite group $G^{\text{op}}$ on X .
[src:group-theory/group-action] Thus, for establishing general properties of a single group action, it suffices to consider only left actions.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action is called *faithful* or *effective* if $g\cdot x=x$ for all $x\in X$ implies that $g=e_{G}$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] Equivalently, the homomorphism from G to the group of bijections of X corresponding to the action is injective.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action is called *free* (or *semiregular* or *fixed-point free*) if the statement that $g\cdot x=x$ for some $x\in X$ already implies that $g=e_{G}$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] In other words, no non-trivial element of G fixes a point of X .
[src:group-theory/group-action] This is a much stronger property than faithfulness.
[src:group-theory/group-action] For example, the action of any group on itself by left multiplication is free.
[src:group-theory/group-action] This observation implies Cayley's theorem that any group can be embedded in a symmetric group (which is infinite when the group is).
[src:group-theory/group-action] A finite group may act faithfully on a set of size much smaller than its cardinality (however such an action cannot be free).
[src:group-theory/group-action] For instance the abelian 2-group $(\mathbb {Z} /2\mathbb {Z} )^{n}$ (of cardinality $2^{n}$ ) acts faithfully on a set of size $2n$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] This is not always the case, for example the cyclic group $\mathbb {Z} /2^{n}\mathbb {Z}$ cannot act faithfully on a set of size less than $2^{n}$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] In general, the smallest set on which a faithful action can be defined can vary greatly for groups of the same size.
[src:group-theory/group-action] For example, three groups of size 120 are the symmetric group $S_{5}$ , the icosahedral group $A_{5}\times \mathbb {Z} /2\mathbb {Z}$ and the cyclic group $\mathbb {Z} /120\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] The smallest sets on which faithful actions can be defined for these groups are of size 5, 7, and 16 respectively.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action of G on X is called *transitive* if for any two points $x,y\in X$ there exists a $g\in G$ so that $g\cdot x=y$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action is *simply transitive* (or *sharply transitive*, or *regular*) if it is both transitive and free.
[src:group-theory/group-action] This means that given $x,y\in X$ there is exactly one $g\in G$ such that $g\cdot x=y$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] If X is acted upon simply transitively by a group G then it is called a principal homogeneous space for G or a G -torsor.
[src:group-theory/group-action] In other words, the action on the subset of $X^{n}$ of tuples without repeated entries is transitive.
[src:group-theory/group-action] For $n=2,3$ this is often called double, respectively triple, transitivity.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The class of 2-transitive groups (that is, subgroups of a finite symmetric group whose action is 2-transitive) and more generally multiply transitive groups is well-studied in finite group theory.
[src:group-theory/group-action] An action is *sharply n -transitive* when the action on tuples without repeated entries in $X^{n}$ is sharply transitive.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action of the symmetric group of X is transitive, in fact n -transitive for any n up to the cardinality of X .
[src:group-theory/group-action] If X has cardinality n , the action of the alternating group is $(n-2)$ -transitive but not $(n-1)$ -transitive.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action of the general linear group of a vector space V on the set $V\setminus \{0\}$ of non-zero vectors is transitive, but not 2-transitive (similarly for the action of the special linear group if the dimension of V is at least 2).
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action of the orthogonal group of a Euclidean space is not transitive on nonzero vectors but it is on the unit sphere.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action of G on X is called *primitive* if there is no partition of X preserved by all elements of G apart from the trivial partitions (the partition in a single piece and its dual, the partition into singletons).
[src:group-theory/group-action] Assume that X is a topological space and the action of G is by homeomorphisms.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action is *wandering* if every $x\in X$ has a neighbourhood U such that there are only finitely many $g\in G$ with $(g\cdot U)\cap U\neq \emptyset$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] More generally, a point $x\in X$ is called a point of discontinuity for the action of G if there is an open subset $U\ni x$ such that there are only finitely many $g\in G$ with $(g\cdot U)\cap U\neq \emptyset$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] The *domain of discontinuity* of the action is the set of all points of discontinuity.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Equivalently it is the largest G -stable open subset $\Omega \subset X$ such that the action of G on $\Omega$ is wandering.
[src:group-theory/group-action] In a dynamical context this is also called a *wandering set*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action is *properly discontinuous* if for every compact subset $K\subset X$ there are only finitely many $g\in G$ such that $(g\cdot K)\cap K\neq \emptyset$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] This is strictly stronger than wandering; for instance the action of $\mathbb {Z}$ on $\mathbb {R} ^{2}\backslash \{(0,0)\}$ given by $n\cdot (x,y)=(2^{n}x,2^{-n}y)$ is wandering and free but not properly discontinuous.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action by deck transformations of the fundamental group of a locally simply connected space on a universal cover is wandering and free.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Such actions can be characterized by the following property: every $x\in X$ has a neighbourhood U such that $(g\cdot U)\cap U=\emptyset$ for every $g\in G\backslash \{e_{G}\}$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] Actions with this property are sometimes called *freely discontinuous*, and the largest subset on which the action is freely discontinuous is then called the *free regular set*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] An action of a group G on a locally compact space X is called *cocompact* if there exists a compact subset $A\subset X$ such that $X=G\cdot A$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] For a properly discontinuous action, cocompactness is equivalent to compactness of the quotient space $X/G$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] Now assume G is a topological group and X a topological space on which it acts by homeomorphisms.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action is said to be *continuous* if the map $G\times X\rightarrow X$ is continuous for the product topology.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action is said to be *proper* if the map $G\times X\rightarrow X\times X$ defined by $(g,x)\mapsto (x,g\cdot x)$ is proper.
[src:group-theory/group-action] This means that given compact sets $K,K'$ the set of $g\in G$ such that $(g\cdot K)\cap K'\neq \varnothing$ is compact.
[src:group-theory/group-action] In particular, this is equivalent to proper discontinuity if G is a discrete group.
[src:group-theory/group-action] It is said to be *locally free* if there exists a neighbourhood U of $e_{G}$ such that $g\cdot x\neq x$ for all $x\in X$ and $g\in U\setminus \{e_{G}\}$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action is said to be *strongly continuous* if the orbital map $g\mapsto g\cdot x$ is continuous for every $x\in X$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] Contrary to what the name suggests, this is a weaker property than continuity of the action.
[src:group-theory/group-action] If G is a Lie group and X a differentiable manifold, then the subspace of *smooth points* for the action is the set of points $x\in X$ such that the map $g\mapsto g\cdot x$ is smooth.
[src:group-theory/group-action] There is a well-developed theory of Lie group actions, i.e. action which are smooth on the whole space.
[src:group-theory/group-action] If *g* acts by linear transformations on a module over a commutative ring, the action is said to be irreducible if there are no proper nonzero *g*-invariant submodules.
[src:group-theory/group-action] It is said to be *semisimple* if it decomposes as a direct sum of irreducible actions.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Consider a group *G* acting on a set *X*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The *orbit* of an element *x* in *X* is the set of elements in *X* to which *x* can be moved by the elements of *G*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The defining properties of a group guarantee that the set of orbits of (points *x* in) *X* under the action of *G* form a partition of *X*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The associated equivalence relation is defined by saying *x* ~ *y* if and only if there exists a *g* in *G* with *g*⋅*x* = *y*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The orbits are then the equivalence classes under this relation; two elements *x* and *y* are equivalent if and only if their orbits are the same, that is, *G*⋅*x* = *G*⋅*y*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The group action is transitive if and only if it has exactly one orbit, that is, if there exists *x* in *X* with *G*⋅*x* = *X*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] This is the case if and only if *G*⋅*x* = *X* for *all* *x* in *X* (given that *X* is non-empty).
[src:group-theory/group-action] The set of all orbits of *X* under the action of *G* is written as *X* / *G* (or, less frequently, as *G* \ *X*), and is called the *quotient* of the action.
[src:group-theory/group-action] In geometric situations it may be called the *orbit space*, while in algebraic situations it may be called the space of *coinvariants*, and written *X**G*, by contrast with the invariants (fixed points), denoted *X**G*: the coinvariants are a *quotient* while the invariants are a *subset*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The coinvariant terminology and notation are used particularly in group cohomology and group homology, which use the same superscript/subscript convention.
[src:group-theory/group-action] If Y is a subset of X , then $G\cdot Y$ denotes the set $\{g\cdot y\mid g\in G,y\in Y\}$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] The subset Y is said to be *invariant under* G if $G\cdot Y=Y$ (which is equivalent $G\cdot Y\subseteq Y$ ).
[src:group-theory/group-action] In that case, G also operates on Y by restricting the action to Y .
[src:group-theory/group-action] The subset Y is called *fixed under* G if $g\cdot y=y$ for all g in G and all y in Y .
[src:group-theory/group-action] Every subset that is fixed under G is also invariant under G , but not conversely.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Every orbit is an invariant subset of X on which G acts transitively.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Conversely, any invariant subset of X is a union of orbits.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action of G on X is *transitive* if and only if all elements are equivalent, meaning that there is only one orbit.
[src:group-theory/group-action] A G *-invariant* element of X is $x\in X$ such that $g\cdot x=x$ for all $g\in G$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] The set of all such x is denoted $X^{G}$ and called the G *-invariants* of X .
[src:group-theory/group-action] When X is a G -module, $X^{G}$ is the zeroth cohomology group of G with coefficients in X , and the higher cohomology groups are the derived functors of the functor of G -invariants.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Given g in G and x in X with $g\cdot x=x$ , it is said that " x is a fixed point of g " or that " g fixes x ".
[src:group-theory/group-action] For every x in X , the **stabilizer subgroup** of G with respect to x (also called the **isotropy group** or **little group**) is the set of all elements in G that fix x : $G_{x}=\{g\in G:g{\cdot }x=x\}.$ This is a subgroup of G , though typically not a normal one.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The action of G on X is free if and only if all stabilizers are trivial.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The kernel N of the homomorphism with the symmetric group, $G\rightarrow \operatorname {Sym} (X)$ , is given by the intersection of the stabilizers $G_{x}$ for all x in X .
[src:group-theory/group-action] If N is trivial, the action is said to be faithful (or effective).
[src:group-theory/group-action] Let x and y be two elements in X , and let g be a group element such that $y=g\cdot x$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] Proof: by definition, $h\in G_{y}$ if and only if $h\cdot (g\cdot x)=g\cdot x$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] An opposite inclusion follows similarly by taking $h\in G_{x}$ and $x=g^{-1}\cdot y$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] The above says that the stabilizers of elements in the same orbit are conjugate to each other.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Thus, to each orbit, we can associate a conjugacy class of a subgroup of G (that is, the set of all conjugates of the subgroup).
[src:group-theory/group-action] Let $(H)$ denote the conjugacy class of H .
[src:group-theory/group-action] Then the orbit O has type $(H)$ if the stabilizer $G_{x}$ of some/any x in O belongs to $(H)$ .
[src:group-theory/group-action] A maximal orbit type is often called a principal orbit type.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Orbits and stabilizers are closely related.
[src:group-theory/group-action] For a fixed *x* in *X*, consider the map *f* : *G* → *X* given by *g* ↦ *g*⋅*x*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] By definition the image *f*(*G*) of this map is the orbit *G*⋅*x*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The condition for two elements to have the same image is $f(g)=f(h)\iff g{\cdot }x=h{\cdot }x\iff g^{-1}h{\cdot }x=x\iff g^{-1}h\in G_{x}\iff h\in gG_{x}.$ In other words, *f*(*g*) = *f*(*h*) *if and only if* *g* and *h* lie in the same coset for the stabilizer subgroup *G**x*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Thus, the fiber *f*−1({*y*}) of *f* over any *y* in *G*⋅*x* is contained in such a coset, and every such coset also occurs as a fiber.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Therefore *f* induces a *bijection* between the set *G* / *G**x* of cosets for the stabilizer subgroup and the orbit *G*⋅*x*, which sends *gG**x* ↦ *g*⋅*x*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] This result is known as the *orbit–stabilizer theorem*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] If *G* is finite then the orbit–stabilizer theorem, together with Lagrange's theorem, gives $|G\cdot x|=[G\,:\,G_{x}]=|G|/|G_{x}|.$ In other words, the length of the orbit of *x* times the order of its stabilizer is the order of the group.
[src:group-theory/group-action] In particular that implies that the orbit length is a divisor of the group order.
[src:group-theory/group-action] This result is especially useful since it can be employed for counting arguments (typically in situations where *X* is finite as well).
[src:group-theory/group-action] , and this action is transitive as can be seen by composing rotations about the center of the cube.
[src:group-theory/group-action] that fixes 1 must send 2 to either 2, 4, or 5.
[src:group-theory/group-action] , which permutes 2, 4, 5 and 3, 6, 8, and fixes 1 and 7.
[src:group-theory/group-action] that fixes 1 and 2 must send 3 to either 3 or 6.
[src:group-theory/group-action] fixing 1, 2 and 3 must also fix all other vertices, since they are determined by their adjacency to 1, 2 and 3.
[src:group-theory/group-action] A result closely related to the orbit–stabilizer theorem is Burnside's lemma: $|X/G|={\frac {1}{|G|}}\sum _{g\in G}|X^{g}|,$ where *X**g* is the set of points fixed by *g*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] This result is mainly of use when *G* and *X* are finite, when it can be interpreted as follows: the number of orbits is equal to the average number of points fixed per group element.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Fixing a group *G*, the set of formal differences of finite *G*-sets forms a ring called the Burnside ring of *G*, where addition corresponds to disjoint union, and multiplication to Cartesian product.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The notion of group action can be encoded by the *action groupoid* *G*′ = *G* ⋉ *X* associated to the group action.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The stabilizers of the action are the vertex groups of the groupoid and the orbits of the action are its components.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Morphisms of *G*-sets are also called *equivariant maps* or *G*-*maps*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] The composition of two morphisms is again a morphism.
[src:group-theory/group-action] If a morphism *f* is bijective, then its inverse is also a morphism.
[src:group-theory/group-action] In this case *f* is called an *isomorphism*, and the two *G*-sets *X* and *Y* are called *isomorphic*; for all practical purposes, isomorphic *G*-sets are indistinguishable.
[src:group-theory/group-action] With this notion of morphism, the collection of all *G*-sets forms a category; this category is a Grothendieck topos (in fact, assuming a classical metalogic, this topos will even be Boolean).
[src:group-theory/group-action] We can also consider actions of monoids on sets, by using the same two axioms as above.
[src:group-theory/group-action] This does not define bijective maps and equivalence relations however.
[src:group-theory/group-action] Instead of actions on sets, we can define actions of groups and monoids on objects of an arbitrary category: start with an object *X* of some category, and then define an action on *X* as a monoid homomorphism into the monoid of endomorphisms of *X*.
[src:group-theory/group-action] If *X* has an underlying set, then all definitions and facts stated above can be carried over.
[src:group-theory/group-action] For example, if we take the category of vector spaces, we obtain group representations in this fashion.
[src:group-theory/group-action] We can view a group *G* as a category with a single object in which every morphism is invertible.
[src:group-theory/group-action] A (left) group action is then nothing but a (covariant) functor from *G* to the category of sets, and a group representation is a functor from *G* to the category of vector spaces.
[src:group-theory/group-action] A morphism between *G*-sets is then a natural transformation between the group action functors.
[src:group-theory/group-action] In analogy, an action of a groupoid is a functor from the groupoid to the category of sets or to some other category.
[src:group-theory/group-action] In addition to continuous actions of topological groups on topological spaces, one also often considers smooth actions of Lie groups on smooth manifolds, regular actions of algebraic groups on algebraic varieties, and actions of group schemes on schemes.
[src:group-theory/group-action] All of these are examples of group objects acting on objects of their respective category.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **group** is a set with an operation that combines any two elements of the set to produce a third element within the same set and the following conditions must hold: the operation is associative, it has an identity element, and every element of the set has an inverse element.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, the integers with the addition operation form a group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The concept of a group was elaborated for handling, in a unified way, many mathematical structures such as numbers, geometric shapes and polynomial roots.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Because the concept of groups is ubiquitous in numerous areas both within and outside mathematics, some authors consider it as a central organizing principle of contemporary mathematics.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In geometry, groups arise naturally in the study of symmetries and geometric transformations: the symmetries of an object form a group, called the symmetry group of the object, and the transformations of a given type form a general group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Lie groups appear in symmetry groups in geometry, and also in the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The Poincaré group is a Lie group consisting of the symmetries of spacetime in special relativity.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Point groups describe symmetry in molecular chemistry.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The concept of a group arose in the study of polynomial equations. Évariste Galois, in the 1830s, introduced the term *group* (French: *groupe*) for the symmetry group of the roots of an equation, now called a Galois group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] After contributions from other fields such as number theory and geometry, the group notion was generalized and firmly established around 1870.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Modern group theory—an active mathematical discipline—studies groups in their own right.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] To explore groups, mathematicians have devised various notions to break groups into smaller, better-understandable pieces, such as subgroups, quotient groups and simple groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In addition to their abstract properties, group theorists also study the different ways in which a group can be expressed concretely, both from a point of view of representation theory (that is, through the representations of the group) and of computational group theory.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] A theory has been developed for finite groups, which culminated with the classification of finite simple groups, completed in 2004.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Since the mid-1980s, geometric group theory, which studies finitely generated groups as geometric objects, has become an active area in group theory.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] One of the more familiar groups is the set of integers $\mathbb {Z} =\{\ldots ,-4,-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3,4,\ldots \}$ together with addition.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For any two integers a and ⁠ b ⁠, the sum $a+b$ is also an integer; this *closure* property says that + is a binary operation on ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The following properties of integer addition serve as a model for the group axioms in the definition below.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The integers, together with the operation ⁠ + ⁠, form a mathematical object belonging to a broad class sharing similar structural aspects.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] To appropriately understand these structures as a collective, the following definition is developed.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Note: Uniqueness of the identity and uniqueness of inverse elements are not part of the axioms; they are *consequences* of the three axioms.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Formally, a group is an ordered pair of a set and a binary operation on this set that satisfies the group axioms.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The set is called the *underlying set* of the group, and the operation is called the *group operation* or the *group law*.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] A group and its underlying set are thus two different mathematical objects.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] To avoid cumbersome notation, it is common to abuse notation by using the same symbol to denote both.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] This reflects also an informal way of thinking: that the group is the same as the set except that it has been enriched by additional structure provided by the operation.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, consider the set of real numbers ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠, which has the operations of addition $a+b$ and multiplication ⁠ $ab$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Formally, $\mathbb {R}$ is a set, $(\mathbb {R} ,+)$ is a group, and $(\mathbb {R} ,+,\cdot )$ is a field.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] But it is common to write $\mathbb {R}$ to denote any of these three objects.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The *additive group* of the field $\mathbb {R}$ is the group whose underlying set is $\mathbb {R}$ and whose operation is addition.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The *multiplicative group* of the field $\mathbb {R}$ is the group $\mathbb {R} ^{\times }$ whose underlying set is the set of nonzero real numbers $\mathbb {R} \smallsetminus \{0\}$ and whose operation is multiplication.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] More generally, one speaks of an *additive group* whenever the group operation is notated as addition; in this case, the identity is typically denoted ⁠ 0 ⁠, and the inverse of an element x is denoted ⁠ $-x$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Similarly, one speaks of a *multiplicative group* whenever the group operation is notated as multiplication; in this case, the identity is typically denoted ⁠ 1 ⁠, and the inverse of an element x is denoted ⁠ $x^{-1}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In a multiplicative group, the operation symbol is usually omitted entirely, so that the operation is denoted by juxtaposition, $ab$ instead of ⁠ $a\cdot b$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The definition of a group does not require that $a\cdot b=b\cdot a$ for all elements a and b in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] If this additional condition holds, then the operation is said to be commutative, and the group is called an abelian group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] It is a common convention that for an abelian group either additive or multiplicative notation may be used, but for a nonabelian group only multiplicative notation is used.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Several other notations are commonly used for groups whose elements are not numbers.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For a group whose elements are functions, the operation is often function composition ⁠ $f\circ g$ ⁠; then the identity may be denoted id.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In the more specific cases of geometric transformation groups, symmetry groups, permutation groups, and automorphism groups, the symbol $\circ$ is often omitted, as for multiplicative groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Many other variants of notation may be encountered.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Vertices are identified by color or number.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Two figures in the plane are congruent if one can be changed into the other using a combination of rotations, reflections, and translations.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] However, some figures are congruent to themselves in more than one way, and these extra congruences are called symmetries.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Each sends a point in the square to the corresponding point under the symmetry.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, $r_{1}$ sends a point to its rotation 90° clockwise around the square's center, and $f_{\mathrm {h} }$ sends a point to its reflection across the square's vertical middle line.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Composing two of these symmetries gives another symmetry.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] These symmetries determine a group called the dihedral group of degree four, denoted ⁠ $\mathrm {D} _{4}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The underlying set of the group is the above set of symmetries, and the group operation is function composition.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Two symmetries are combined by composing them as functions, that is, applying the first one to the square, and the second one to the result of the first application.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The result of performing first a and then b is written symbolically *from right to left* as $b\circ a$ ("apply the symmetry b after performing the symmetry ⁠ a ⁠").
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] This is the usual notation for the composition of functions.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] A Cayley table lists the results of all such compositions possible.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, rotating by 270° clockwise (⁠ $r_{3}$ ⁠) and then reflecting horizontally (⁠ $f_{\mathrm {h} }$ ⁠) is the same as performing a reflection along the diagonal (⁠ $f_{\mathrm {d} }$ ⁠).
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In contrast to the group of integers above, where the order of the operation is immaterial, it does matter in ⁠ $\mathrm {D} _{4}$ ⁠, as, for example, $f_{\mathrm {h} }\circ r_{1}=f_{\mathrm {c} }$ but ⁠ $r_{1}\circ f_{\mathrm {h} }=f_{\mathrm {d} }$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In other words, $\mathrm {D} _{4}$ is not abelian.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The modern concept of an abstract group developed out of several fields of mathematics.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The original motivation for group theory was the quest for solutions of polynomial equations of degree higher than 4.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The 19th-century French mathematician Évariste Galois, extending prior work of Paolo Ruffini and Joseph-Louis Lagrange, gave a criterion for the solvability of a particular polynomial equation in terms of the symmetry group of its roots (solutions).
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The elements of such a Galois group correspond to certain permutations of the roots.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] At first, Galois's ideas were rejected by his contemporaries, and published only posthumously.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] More general permutation groups were investigated in particular by Augustin Louis Cauchy.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Arthur Cayley's *On the theory of groups, as depending on the symbolic equation $\theta ^{n}=1$* (1854) gives the first abstract definition of a finite group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Geometry was a second field in which groups were used systematically, especially symmetry groups as part of Felix Klein's 1872 Erlangen program.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] After novel geometries such as hyperbolic and projective geometry had emerged, Klein used group theory to organize them in a more coherent way.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Further advancing these ideas, Sophus Lie founded the study of Lie groups in 1884.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The third field contributing to group theory was number theory.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Certain abelian group structures had been used implicitly in Carl Friedrich Gauss's number-theoretical work *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae* (1798), and more explicitly by Leopold Kronecker.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In 1847, Ernst Kummer made early attempts to prove Fermat's Last Theorem by developing groups describing factorization into prime numbers.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The theory of Lie groups, and more generally locally compact groups was studied by Hermann Weyl, Élie Cartan and many others.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Its algebraic counterpart, the theory of algebraic groups, was first shaped by Claude Chevalley (from the late 1930s) and later by the work of Armand Borel and Jacques Tits.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The University of Chicago's 1960–61 Group Theory Year brought together group theorists such as Daniel Gorenstein, John G.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Thompson and Walter Feit, laying the foundation of a collaboration that, with input from numerous other mathematicians, led to the classification of finite simple groups, with the final step taken by Aschbacher and Smith in 2004.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] This project exceeded previous mathematical endeavours by its sheer size, in both length of proof and number of researchers.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Research concerning this classification proof is ongoing.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Group theory remains a highly active mathematical branch, impacting many other fields, as the examples below illustrate.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Basic facts about all groups that can be obtained directly from the group axioms are commonly subsumed under *elementary group theory*.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, repeated applications of the associativity axiom show that the unambiguity of $a\cdot b\cdot c=(a\cdot b)\cdot c=a\cdot (b\cdot c)$ generalizes to more than three factors (for example, $a\cdot b\cdot c\cdot d$ is also unambiguous).
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Because this implies that parentheses can be inserted anywhere within such a series of terms, parentheses are usually omitted.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The group axioms imply that the identity element is unique; that is, there exists only one identity element: any two identity elements e and f of a group are equal, because the group axioms imply ⁠ $e=e\cdot f=f$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] It is thus customary to speak of *the* identity element of the group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The group axioms also imply that the inverse of each element is unique.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Let a group element a have both b and c as inverses.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Therefore, it is customary to speak of *the* inverse of an element.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Given elements a and b of a group G , there is a unique solution x in G to the equation $a\cdot x=b$ , namely $a^{-1}\cdot b$ .
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] It follows that for each a in G , the function $G\to G$ that maps each x to $a\cdot x$ is a bijection; it is called *left multiplication* by a or *left translation* by a .
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Similarly, given a and b in G , the unique solution x to $x\cdot a=b$ is $b\cdot a^{-1}$ .
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For each a , the function $G\to G$ that maps each x to $x\cdot a$ is a bijection called *right multiplication* by a or *right translation* by a .
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The group axioms for identity and inverses may be "weakened" to assert only the existence of a left identity and left inverses.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] From these *one-sided axioms*, one can prove that the left identity is also a right identity and a left inverse is also a right inverse for the same element.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Since they define exactly the same structures as groups, collectively the axioms are not weaker.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In particular, assuming associativity and the existence of a left identity e (that is, ⁠ $e\cdot f=f$ ⁠) and a left inverse $f^{-1}$ for each element f (that is, ⁠ $f^{-1}\cdot f=e$ ⁠), it follows that every left inverse is also a right inverse of the same element as follows.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] These results do not hold if any of these axioms (associativity, existence of left identity and existence of left inverse) is removed.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For a structure with a looser definition (like a semigroup) one may have, for example, that a left identity is not necessarily a right identity.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The same result can be obtained by only assuming the existence of a right identity and a right inverse.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] However, only assuming the existence of a *left* identity and a *right* inverse (or vice versa) is not sufficient to define a group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, consider the set $G=\{e,f\}$ with the operator $\,\!\cdot$ satisfying $e\cdot e=f\cdot e=e$ and ⁠ $e\cdot f=f\cdot f=f$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] This structure does have a left identity (namely, ⁠ e ⁠), and each element has a right inverse (which is e for both elements).
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Furthermore, this operation is associative (since the product of any number of elements is always equal to the rightmost element in that product, regardless of the order in which these operations are applied).
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] However, $(G,\cdot )$ is not a group, since it lacks a right identity.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] When studying sets, one uses concepts such as subset, function, and quotient by an equivalence relation.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] When studying groups, one uses instead subgroups, homomorphisms, and quotient groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] These are the analogues that take the group structure into account.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Group homomorphisms are functions that respect group structure; they may be used to relate two groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] It would be natural to require also that $\varphi$ respect identities, ⁠ $\varphi (1_{G})=1_{H}$ ⁠, and inverses, $\varphi (a^{-1})=\varphi (a)^{-1}$ for all a in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] However, these additional requirements need not be included in the definition of homomorphisms, because they are already implied by the requirement of respecting the group operation.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The *identity homomorphism* of a group G is the homomorphism $\iota _{G}:G\to G$ that maps each element of G to itself.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] An *isomorphism* is a homomorphism that has an inverse homomorphism; equivalently, it is a bijective homomorphism.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Groups G and H are called *isomorphic* if there exists an isomorphism ⁠ $\varphi :G\to H$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In this case, H can be obtained from G simply by renaming its elements according to the function ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠; then any statement true for G is true for ⁠ H ⁠, provided that any specific elements mentioned in the statement are also renamed.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The collection of all groups, together with the homomorphisms between them, form a category, the category of groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] An injective homomorphism $\phi :G'\to G$ factors canonically as an isomorphism followed by an inclusion, $G'\;{\stackrel {\sim }{\to }}\;H\hookrightarrow G$ for some subgroup ⁠ H ⁠ of ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Injective homomorphisms are the monomorphisms in the category of groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Informally, a *subgroup* is a group H contained within a bigger one, ⁠ G ⁠: it has a subset of the elements of ⁠ G ⁠, with the same operation.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Concretely, this means that the identity element of G must be contained in ⁠ H ⁠, and whenever $h_{1}$ and $h_{2}$ are both in ⁠ H ⁠, then so are $h_{1}\cdot h_{2}$ and ⁠ $h_{1}^{-1}$ ⁠, so the elements of ⁠ H ⁠, equipped with the group operation on G restricted to ⁠ H ⁠, indeed form a group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In this case, the inclusion map $H\to G$ is a homomorphism.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The subgroup test provides a necessary and sufficient condition for a nonempty subset ⁠ H ⁠ of a group ⁠ G ⁠ to be a subgroup: it is sufficient to check that $g^{-1}\cdot h\in H$ for all elements g and h in ⁠ H ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Knowing a group's subgroups is important in understanding the group as a whole.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Given any subset S of a group ⁠ G ⁠, the subgroup generated by S consists of all products of elements of S and their inverses.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] It is the smallest subgroup of G containing ⁠ S ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In the example of symmetries of a square, the subgroup generated by $r_{2}$ and $f_{\mathrm {v} }$ consists of these two elements, the identity element ⁠ $\mathrm {id}$ ⁠, and the element ⁠ $f_{\mathrm {h} }=f_{\mathrm {v} }\cdot r_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Again, this is a subgroup, because combining any two of these four elements or their inverses (which are, in this particular case, these same elements) yields an element of this subgroup.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In many situations it is desirable to consider two group elements the same if they differ by an element of a given subgroup.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Cosets are used to formalize this insight: a subgroup H determines left and right cosets, which can be thought of as translations of H by an arbitrary group element ⁠ g ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The left cosets of any subgroup H form a partition of ⁠ G ⁠; that is, the union of all left cosets is equal to G and two left cosets are either equal or have an empty intersection.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The first case $g_{1}H=g_{2}H$ happens precisely when ⁠ $g_{1}^{-1}\cdot g_{2}\in H$ ⁠, i.e., when the two elements differ by an element of ⁠ H ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Similar considerations apply to the right cosets of ⁠ H ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The left cosets of H may or may not be the same as its right cosets.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] If they are (that is, if all g in G satisfy ⁠ $gH=Hg$ ⁠), then H is said to be a *normal subgroup*.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The subgroup R is normal, because $f_{\mathrm {c} }R=U=Rf_{\mathrm {c} }$ and similarly for the other elements of the group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Suppose that N is a normal subgroup of a group ⁠ G ⁠, and $G/N=\{gN\mid g\in G\}$ denotes its set of cosets.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Then there is a unique group law on $G/N$ for which the map $G\to G/N$ sending each element g to $gN$ is a homomorphism.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Explicitly, the product of two cosets $gN$ and $hN$ is ⁠ $(gh)N$ ⁠, the coset $eN=N$ serves as the identity of ⁠ $G/N$ ⁠, and the inverse of $gN$ in the quotient group is ⁠ $(gN)^{-1}=\left(g^{-1}\right)N$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The group ⁠ $G/N$ ⁠, read as "⁠ G ⁠ modulo ⁠ N ⁠", is called a *quotient group* or *factor group*.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The quotient group can alternatively be characterized by a universal property.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The elements of the quotient group $\mathrm {D} _{4}/R$ are R and ⁠ $U=f_{\mathrm {v} }R$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The group operation on the quotient is shown in the table.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Sometimes a group can be reconstructed from a subgroup and quotient (plus some additional data), by the semidirect product construction; $\mathrm {D} _{4}$ is an example.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The first isomorphism theorem implies that any surjective homomorphism $\phi :G\to H$ factors canonically as a quotient homomorphism followed by an isomorphism: ⁠ $G\to G/\ker \phi \;{\stackrel {\sim }{\to }}\;H$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Surjective homomorphisms are the epimorphisms in the category of groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Every group is isomorphic to a quotient of a free group, in many ways.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, the dihedral group $\mathrm {D} _{4}$ is generated by the right rotation $r_{1}$ and the reflection $f_{\mathrm {v} }$ in a vertical line (every element of $\mathrm {D} _{4}$ is a finite product of copies of these and their inverses).
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Hence there is a surjective homomorphism ⁠ $\phi$ ⁠ from the free group $\langle r,f\rangle$ on two generators to $\mathrm {D} _{4}$ sending r to $r_{1}$ and f to ⁠ $f_{1}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In fact, it turns out that $\ker \phi$ is the smallest normal subgroup of $\langle r,f\rangle$ containing these three elements; in other words, all relations are consequences of these three.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The quotient of the free group by this normal subgroup is denoted ⁠ $\langle r,f\mid r^{4}=f^{2}=(r\cdot f)^{2}=1\rangle$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] This is called a *presentation* of $\mathrm {D} _{4}$ by generators and relations, because the first isomorphism theorem for ⁠ $\phi$ ⁠ yields an isomorphism ⁠ $\langle r,f\mid r^{4}=f^{2}=(r\cdot f)^{2}=1\rangle \to \mathrm {D} _{4}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] A presentation of a group can be used to construct the Cayley graph, a graphical depiction of a discrete group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Examples and applications of groups abound.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] A starting point is the group $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers with addition as group operation, introduced above.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] If, instead of addition, multiplication is considered, one obtains multiplicative groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] These groups are predecessors of important constructions in abstract algebra.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Groups are also applied in many other mathematical areas.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Mathematical objects are often examined by associating groups to them and studying the properties of the corresponding groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, Henri Poincaré founded what is now called algebraic topology by introducing the fundamental group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] By means of this connection, topological properties such as proximity and continuity translate into properties of groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Elements of the fundamental group of a topological space are equivalence classes of loops, where loops are considered equivalent if one can be smoothly deformed into another, and the group operation is "concatenation" (tracing one loop then the other).
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, as shown in the figure, if the topological space is the plane with one point removed, then loops which do not wrap around the missing point (blue) can be smoothly contracted to a single point and are the identity element of the fundamental group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] A loop which wraps around the missing point k times cannot be deformed into a loop which wraps m times (with ⁠ $m\neq k$ ⁠), because the loop cannot be smoothly deformed across the hole, so each class of loops is characterized by its winding number around the missing point.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The resulting group is isomorphic to the integers under addition.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In more recent applications, the influence has also been reversed to motivate geometric constructions by a group-theoretical background.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In a similar vein, geometric group theory employs geometric concepts, for example in the study of hyperbolic groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Further branches crucially applying groups include algebraic geometry and number theory.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In addition to the above theoretical applications, many practical applications of groups exist.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Cryptography relies on the combination of the abstract group theory approach together with algorithmical knowledge obtained in computational group theory, in particular when implemented for finite groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Applications of group theory are not restricted to mathematics; sciences such as physics, chemistry and computer science benefit from the concept.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Many number systems, such as the integers and the rationals, enjoy a naturally given group structure.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In some cases, such as with the rationals, both addition and multiplication operations give rise to group structures.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Such number systems are predecessors to more general algebraic structures known as rings and fields.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Further abstract algebraic concepts such as modules, vector spaces and algebras also form groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The group of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ under addition, denoted ⁠ $\left(\mathbb {Z} ,+\right)$ ⁠, has been described above.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The integers, with the operation of multiplication instead of addition, $\left(\mathbb {Z} ,\cdot \right)$ do *not* form a group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The associativity and identity axioms are satisfied, but inverses do not exist: for example, $a=2$ is an integer, but the only solution to the equation $a\cdot b=1$ in this case is ⁠ $b={\tfrac {1}{2}}$ ⁠, which is a rational number, but not an integer.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Hence not every element of $\mathbb {Z}$ has a (multiplicative) inverse.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Fractions of integers (with b nonzero) are known as rational numbers.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The set of all such irreducible fractions is commonly denoted ⁠ $\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] There is still a minor obstacle for ⁠ $\left(\mathbb {Q} ,\cdot \right)$ ⁠, the rationals with multiplication, being a group: because zero does not have a multiplicative inverse (i.e., there is no x such that ⁠ $x\cdot 0=1$ ⁠), $\left(\mathbb {Q} ,\cdot \right)$ is still not a group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] However, the set of all *nonzero* rational numbers $\mathbb {Q} \smallsetminus \left\{0\right\}=\left\{q\in \mathbb {Q} \mid q\neq 0\right\}$ does form an abelian group under multiplication, also denoted ⁠ $\mathbb {Q} ^{\times }$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Associativity and identity element axioms follow from the properties of integers.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The closure requirement still holds true after removing zero, because the product of two nonzero rationals is never zero.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Finally, the inverse of $a/b$ is ⁠ $b/a$ ⁠, therefore the axiom of the inverse element is satisfied.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The rational numbers (including zero) also form a group under addition.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Intertwining addition and multiplication operations yields more complicated structures called rings and – if division by other than zero is possible, such as in $\mathbb {Q}$ – fields, which occupy a central position in abstract algebra.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Group theoretic arguments therefore underlie parts of the theory of those entities.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Modular arithmetic for a *modulus* n defines any two elements a and b that differ by a multiple of n to be equivalent, denoted by ⁠ $a\equiv b{\pmod {n}}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Every integer is equivalent to one of the integers from 0 to ⁠ $n-1$ ⁠, and the operations of modular arithmetic modify normal arithmetic by replacing the result of any operation by its equivalent representative.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Modular addition, defined in this way for the integers from 0 to ⁠ $n-1$ ⁠, forms a group, denoted as $\mathrm {Z} _{n}$ or ⁠ $(\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z} ,+)$ ⁠, with 0 as the identity element and $n-a$ as the inverse element of ⁠ a ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] A familiar example is addition of hours on the face of a clock, where 12 rather than 0 is chosen as the representative of the identity.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] If the hour hand is on 9 and is advanced 4 hours, it ends up on ⁠ 1 ⁠, as shown in the illustration.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For any prime number ⁠ p ⁠, there is also the multiplicative group of integers modulo ⁠ p ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Its elements can be represented by 1 to ⁠ $p-1$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The group operation, multiplication modulo ⁠ p ⁠, replaces the usual product by its representative, the remainder of division by ⁠ p ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, for ⁠ $p=5$ ⁠, the four group elements can be represented by ⁠ $1,2,3,4$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In this group, ⁠ $4\cdot 4\equiv 1{\pmod {5}}$ ⁠, because the usual product $16$ is equivalent to ⁠ 1 ⁠: when divided by 5 it yields a remainder of ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The primality of p ensures that the usual product of two representatives is not divisible by ⁠ p ⁠, and therefore that the modular product is nonzero.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The identity element is represented by ⁠ 1 ⁠, and associativity follows from the corresponding property of the integers.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Finally, the inverse element axiom requires that given an integer a not divisible by ⁠ p ⁠, there exists an integer b such that $a\cdot b\equiv 1{\pmod {p}},$ that is, such that p evenly divides ⁠ $a\cdot b-1$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The inverse b can be found by using Bézout's identity and the fact that the greatest common divisor $\gcd(a,p)$ equals ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In the case $p=5$ above, the inverse of the element represented by 4 is that represented by ⁠ 4 ⁠, and the inverse of the element represented by 3 is represented by ⁠ 2 ⁠, as ⁠ $3\cdot 2=6\equiv 1{\pmod {5}}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] This example is similar to $\left(\mathbb {Q} \smallsetminus \left\{0\right\},\cdot \right)$ above: it consists of exactly those elements in the ring $\mathbb {Z} /p\mathbb {Z}$ that have a multiplicative inverse.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] These groups, denoted ⁠ $\mathbb {F} _{p}^{\times }$ ⁠, are crucial to public-key cryptography.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] A *cyclic group* is a group all of whose elements are powers of a particular element ⁠ a ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Such an element a is called a generator or a primitive element of the group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In the groups $(\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z} ,+)$ introduced above, the element 1 is primitive, so these groups are cyclic.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Indeed, each element is expressible as a sum all of whose terms are ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Any cyclic group with n elements is isomorphic to this group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] A second example for cyclic groups is the group of ⁠ n ⁠th complex roots of unity, given by complex numbers z satisfying ⁠ $z^{n}=1$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] These numbers can be visualized as the vertices on a regular n -gon, as shown in blue in the image for ⁠ $n=6$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The group operation is multiplication of complex numbers.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In the picture, multiplying with z corresponds to a counter-clockwise rotation by 60°.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Some cyclic groups have an infinite number of elements.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In these groups, for every non-zero element ⁠ a ⁠, all the powers of a are distinct; despite the name "cyclic group", the powers of the elements do not cycle.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] An infinite cyclic group is isomorphic to ⁠ $(\mathbb {Z} ,+)$ ⁠, the group of integers under addition introduced above.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] As these two prototypes are both abelian, so are all cyclic groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The study of finitely generated abelian groups is quite mature, including the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups; and reflecting this state of affairs, many group-related notions, such as center and commutator, describe the extent to which a given group is not abelian.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] In chemistry, point groups describe molecular symmetries, while space groups describe crystal symmetries in crystallography.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] These symmetries underlie the chemical and physical behavior of these systems, and group theory enables simplification of quantum mechanical analysis of these properties.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] For example, group theory is used to show that optical transitions between certain quantum levels cannot occur simply because of the symmetry of the states involved.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Group theory helps predict the changes in physical properties that occur when a material undergoes a phase transition, for example, from a cubic to a tetrahedral crystalline form.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Such spontaneous symmetry breaking has found further application in elementary particle physics, where its occurrence is related to the appearance of Goldstone bosons.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Finite symmetry groups such as the Mathieu groups are used in coding theory, which is in turn applied in error correction of transmitted data, and in CD players.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Another application is differential Galois theory, which characterizes functions having antiderivatives of a prescribed form, giving group-theoretic criteria for when solutions of certain differential equations are well-behaved.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Geometric properties that remain stable under group actions are investigated in (geometric) invariant theory.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Matrix groups consist of matrices together with matrix multiplication.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The *general linear group* $\mathrm {GL} (n,\mathbb {R} )$ consists of all invertible ⁠ n ⁠-by-⁠ n ⁠ matrices with real entries.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Its subgroups are referred to as *matrix groups* or *linear groups*.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] The dihedral group example mentioned above can be viewed as a (very small) matrix group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Another important matrix group is the special orthogonal group ⁠ $\mathrm {SO} (n)$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] It describes all possible rotations in n dimensions.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Rotation matrices in this group are used in computer graphics.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] A group action gives further means to study the object being acted on.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, it also yields information about the group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Group representations are an organizing principle in the theory of finite groups, Lie groups, algebraic groups and topological groups, especially (locally) compact groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] Modern Galois theory generalizes the above type of Galois groups by shifting to field theory and considering field extensions formed as the splitting field of a polynomial.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p01] This theory establishes—via the fundamental theorem of Galois theory—a precise relationship between fields and groups, underlining once again the ubiquity of groups in mathematics.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] A group is called *finite* if it has a finite number of elements.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The number of elements is called the order of the group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] An important class is the *symmetric groups* ⁠ $\mathrm {S} _{N}$ ⁠, the groups of permutations of N objects.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] For example, the symmetric group on 3 letters $\mathrm {S} _{3}$ is the group of all possible reorderings of the objects.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The three letters ABC can be reordered into ABC, ACB, BAC, BCA, CAB, CBA, forming in total 6 (factorial of 3) elements.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The group operation is composition of these reorderings, and the identity element is the reordering operation that leaves the order unchanged.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] This class is fundamental insofar as any finite group can be expressed as a subgroup of a symmetric group $\mathrm {S} _{N}$ for a suitable integer ⁠ N ⁠, according to Cayley's theorem.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Parallel to the group of symmetries of the square above, $\mathrm {S} _{3}$ can also be interpreted as the group of symmetries of an equilateral triangle.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The order of an element a in a group G is the least positive integer n such that ⁠ $a^{n}=e$ ⁠, where $a^{n}$ represents $\underbrace {a\cdots a} _{n{\text{ factors}}},$ that is, application of the operation "⁠ $\cdot$ ⁠" to n copies of ⁠ a ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] (If "⁠ $\cdot$ ⁠" represents multiplication, then $a^{n}$ corresponds to the ⁠ n ⁠th power of ⁠ a ⁠.) In infinite groups, such an n may not exist, in which case the order of a is said to be infinity.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The order of an element equals the order of the cyclic subgroup generated by this element.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] More sophisticated counting techniques, for example, counting cosets, yield more precise statements about finite groups: Lagrange's Theorem states that for a finite group G the order of any finite subgroup H divides the order of ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The Sylow theorems give a partial converse.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The dihedral group $\mathrm {D} _{4}$ of symmetries of a square is a finite group of order 8.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] In this group, the order of $r_{1}$ is 4, as is the order of the subgroup R that this element generates.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The order of the reflection elements $f_{\mathrm {v} }$ etc. is 2.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Both orders divide 8, as predicted by Lagrange's theorem.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The groups $\mathbb {F} _{p}^{\times }$ of multiplication modulo a prime p have order ⁠ $p-1$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Any finite abelian group is isomorphic to a product of finite cyclic groups; this statement is part of the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Any group of prime order p is isomorphic to the cyclic group $\mathrm {Z} _{p}$ (a consequence of Lagrange's theorem).
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] But there exist nonabelian groups of order ⁠ $p^{3}$ ⁠; the dihedral group $\mathrm {D} _{4}$ of order $2^{3}$ above is an example.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] When a group G has a normal subgroup N other than $\{1\}$ and G itself, questions about G can sometimes be reduced to questions about N and ⁠ $G/N$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] A nontrivial group is called *simple* if it has no such normal subgroup.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Finite simple groups are to finite groups as prime numbers are to positive integers: they serve as building blocks, in a sense made precise by the Jordan–Hölder theorem.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Computer algebra systems have been used to list all groups of order up to 2000.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] But classifying all finite groups is a problem considered too hard to be solved.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The classification of all finite *simple* groups was a major achievement in contemporary group theory.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] There are several infinite families of such groups, as well as 26 "sporadic groups" that do not belong to any of the families.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The largest sporadic group is called the monster group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The monstrous moonshine conjectures, proved by Richard Borcherds, relate the monster group to certain modular functions.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The gap between the classification of simple groups and the classification of all groups lies in the extension problem.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] An equivalent definition of group consists of replacing the "there exist" part of the group axioms by operations whose result is the element that must exist.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] So, a group is a set G equipped with a binary operation $G\times G\rightarrow G$ (the group operation), a unary operation $G\rightarrow G$ (which provides the inverse) and a nullary operation, which has no operand and results in the identity element.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Otherwise, the group axioms are exactly the same.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] This variant of the definition avoids existential quantifiers and is used in computing with groups and for computer-aided proofs.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] This way of defining groups lends itself to generalizations such as the notion of group object in a category.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Briefly, this is an object with morphisms that mimic the group axioms.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Some topological spaces may be endowed with a group law.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] In order for the group law and the topology to interweave well, the group operations must be continuous functions; informally, $g\cdot h$ and $g^{-1}$ must not vary wildly if g and h vary only a little.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Such groups are called *topological groups,* and they are the group objects in the category of topological spaces.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The most basic examples are the group of real numbers under addition and the group of nonzero real numbers under multiplication.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Similar examples can be formed from any other topological field, such as the field of complex numbers or the field of *p*-adic numbers.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] These examples are locally compact, so they have Haar measures and can be studied via harmonic analysis.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Other locally compact topological groups include the group of points of an algebraic group over a local field or adele ring; these are basic to number theory Galois groups of infinite algebraic field extensions are equipped with the Krull topology, which plays a role in infinite Galois theory.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] A generalization used in algebraic geometry is the étale fundamental group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] A *Lie group* is a group that also has the structure of a differentiable manifold; informally, this means that it looks locally like a Euclidean space of some fixed dimension.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Again, the definition requires the additional structure, here the manifold structure, to be compatible: the multiplication and inverse maps are required to be smooth.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] A standard example is the general linear group introduced above: it is an open subset of the space of all n -by- n matrices, because it is given by the inequality $\det(A)\neq 0,$ where A denotes an n -by- n matrix.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Lie groups are of fundamental importance in modern physics: Noether's theorem links continuous symmetries to conserved quantities.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Rotation, as well as translations in space and time, are basic symmetries of the laws of mechanics.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] They can, for instance, be used to construct simple models—imposing, say, axial symmetry on a situation will typically lead to significant simplification in the equations one needs to solve to provide a physical description.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Another example is the group of Lorentz transformations, which relate measurements of time and velocity of two observers in motion relative to each other.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] They can be deduced in a purely group-theoretical way, by expressing the transformations as a rotational symmetry of Minkowski space.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The latter serves—in the absence of significant gravitation—as a model of spacetime in special relativity.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The full symmetry group of Minkowski space, i.e., including translations, is known as the Poincaré group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] By the above, it plays a pivotal role in special relativity and, by implication, for quantum field theories.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Symmetries that vary with location are central to the modern description of physical interactions with the help of gauge theory.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] An important example of a gauge theory is the Standard Model, which describes three of the four known fundamental forces and classifies all known elementary particles.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] More general structures may be defined by relaxing some of the axioms defining a group.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The table gives a list of several structures generalizing groups.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] For example, if the requirement that every element has an inverse is eliminated, the resulting algebraic structure is called a monoid.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] The natural numbers $\mathbb {N}$ (including zero) under addition form a monoid, as do the nonzero integers under multiplication ⁠ $(\mathbb {Z} \smallsetminus \{0\},\cdot )$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Adjoining inverses of all elements of the monoid $(\mathbb {Z} \smallsetminus \{0\},\cdot )$ produces a group ⁠ $(\mathbb {Q} \smallsetminus \{0\},\cdot )$ ⁠, and likewise adjoining inverses to any (abelian) monoid ⁠ M ⁠ produces a group known as the Grothendieck group of ⁠ M ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] More generally, a groupoid is any small category in which every morphism is an isomorphism.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] In a groupoid, the set of all morphisms in the category is usually not a group, because the composition is only partially defined: ⁠ $fg$ ⁠ is defined only when the source of ⁠ f ⁠ matches the target of ⁠ g ⁠.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Groupoids arise in topology (for instance, the fundamental groupoid) and in the theory of stacks.
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] Finally, it is possible to generalize any of these concepts by replacing the binary operation with an n-ary operation (i.e., an operation taking n arguments, for some nonnegative integer n).
[src:group-theory/group-mathematics-p02] With the proper generalization of the group axioms, this gives a notion of n-ary group.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] In chemistry, a group representation can relate mathematical group elements to symmetric rotations and reflections of molecules.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Representations of groups allow many group-theoretic problems to be reduced to problems in linear algebra.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] In physics, they describe how the symmetry group of a physical system affects the solutions of equations describing that system.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] The term *representation of a group* is also used in a more general sense to mean any "description" of a group as a group of transformations of some mathematical object.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] More formally, a "representation" means a homomorphism from the group to the automorphism group of an object.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] If the object is a vector space we have a *linear representation*.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Some people use *realization* for the general notion and reserve the term *representation* for the special case of linear representations.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] The bulk of this article describes linear representation theory; see the last section for generalizations.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] The representation theory of groups divides into subtheories depending on the kind of group being represented.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] The various theories are quite different in detail, though some basic definitions and concepts are similar.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Representation theory also depends heavily on the type of vector space on which the group acts.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] One distinguishes between finite-dimensional representations and infinite-dimensional ones.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] In the infinite-dimensional case, additional structures are important (e.g. whether or not the space is a Hilbert space, Banach space, etc.).
[src:group-theory/group-representation] One must also consider the type of field over which the vector space is defined.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] The most important case is the field of complex numbers.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] The other important cases are the field of real numbers, finite fields, and fields of p-adic numbers.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] In general, algebraically closed fields are easier to handle than non-algebraically closed ones.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] The characteristic of the field is also significant; many theorems for finite groups depend on the characteristic of the field not dividing the order of the group.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] A **representation** of a group *G* on a vector space *V* over a field *K* is a group homomorphism from *G* to GL(*V*), the general linear group on *V*.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Here *V* is called the **representation space** and the dimension of *V* is called the **dimension** or **degree** of the representation.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] It is common practice to refer to *V* itself as the representation when the homomorphism is clear from the context.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] In the case where *V* is of finite dimension *n* it is common to choose a basis for *V* and identify GL(*V*) with GL(*n*, *K*), the group of $n\times n$ invertible matrices on the field *K*.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] } consisting only of the group's identity element.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] is an equivariant map which is an isomorphism of vector spaces.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Consider the complex number $u=e^{2\pi i/3}$ which has the property $u^{3}=1$ .
[src:group-theory/group-representation] The set $C_{3}=\{1,u,u^{2}\}$ forms a cyclic group under multiplication.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] This representation is faithful because $\rho$ is a one-to-one map.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Then $S_{3}$ acts on V by permutation of the three variables.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] A subspace *W* of *V* that is invariant under the group action is called a *subrepresentation*.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] If *V* has exactly two subrepresentations, namely the zero-dimensional subspace and *V* itself, then the representation is said to be **irreducible**; if it has a proper subrepresentation of nonzero dimension, the representation is said to be **reducible**.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] The representation of dimension zero is considered to be neither reducible nor irreducible, just as the number 1 is considered to be neither composite nor prime.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Under the assumption that the characteristic of the field *K* does not divide the size of the group, representations of finite groups can be decomposed into a direct sum of irreducible subrepresentations (see Maschke's theorem).
[src:group-theory/group-representation] This holds in particular for any representation of a finite group over the complex numbers, since the characteristic of the complex numbers is zero, which never divides the size of a group.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] In the example above, the first two representations given (ρ and σ) are both decomposable into two 1-dimensional subrepresentations (given by span{(1,0)} and span{(0,1)}), while the third representation (τ) is irreducible.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] This condition and the axioms for a group imply that ρ(*g*) is a bijection (or permutation) for all *g* in *G*.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Thus we may equivalently define a permutation representation to be a group homomorphism from G to the symmetric group S*X* of *X*.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] For more information on this topic see the article on group action.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Every group *G* can be viewed as a category with a single object; morphisms in this category are just the elements of *G*.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Given an arbitrary category *C*, a *representation* of *G* in *C* is a functor from *G* to *C*.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Such a functor selects an object *X* in *C* and a group homomorphism from *G* to Aut(*X*), the automorphism group of *X*.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] In the case where *C* is **Vect***K*, the category of vector spaces over a field *K*, this definition is equivalent to a linear representation.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Likewise, a set-theoretic representation is just a representation of *G* in the category of sets.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] When *C* is **Ab**, the category of abelian groups, the objects obtained are called *G*-modules.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] For another example consider the category of topological spaces, **Top**.
[src:group-theory/group-representation] Representations in **Top** are homomorphisms from *G* to the homeomorphism group of a topological space *X*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In abstract algebra, **group theory** studies the algebraic structures known as groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The concept of a group is central to abstract algebra: other well-known algebraic structures, such as rings, fields, and vector spaces, can all be seen as groups endowed with additional operations and axioms.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Groups recur throughout mathematics, and the methods of group theory have influenced many parts of algebra.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Linear algebraic groups and Lie groups are two branches of group theory that have experienced advances and have become subject areas in their own right.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Various physical systems, such as crystals and the hydrogen atom, and three of the four known fundamental forces in the universe, may be modelled by symmetry groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Thus group theory and the closely related representation theory have many important applications in physics, chemistry, and materials science.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Group theory is also central to public key cryptography.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The early history of group theory dates from the 19th century.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] One of the most important mathematical achievements of the 20th century was the collaborative effort, taking up more than 10,000 journal pages and mostly published between 1960 and 2004, that culminated in a complete classification of finite simple groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Group theory has three main historical sources: number theory, the theory of algebraic equations, geometry, and analysis.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The number-theoretic strand was begun by Leonhard Euler, and developed by Gauss's work on modular arithmetic and additive and multiplicative groups related to quadratic fields.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In geometry, groups first became important in projective geometry and, later, non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Felix Klein's Erlangen program proclaimed group theory to be the organizing principle of geometry.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Galois, in the 1830s, was the first to employ groups to determine the solvability of polynomial equations.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Arthur Cayley and Augustin Louis Cauchy pushed these investigations further by creating the theory of permutation groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The second historical source for groups stems from geometrical situations.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In an attempt to come to grips with possible geometries (such as Euclidean, hyperbolic or projective geometry) using group theory, Felix Klein initiated the Erlangen programme.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Sophus Lie, in 1884, started using groups (now called Lie groups) attached to analytic problems.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Thirdly, groups were, at first implicitly and later explicitly, used in algebraic number theory.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The different scopes of these early sources resulted in different notions of groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The theory of groups was unified starting around 1880.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Since then, the impact of group theory has been ever-growing, giving rise to the birth of abstract algebra in the early 20th century, representation theory, and many more influential spin-off domains.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The classification of finite simple groups is a vast body of work from the mid 20th century, classifying all the finite simple groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The range of groups being considered has gradually expanded from finite permutation groups and special examples of matrix groups to abstract groups that may be specified through a presentation by generators and relations.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The first class of groups to undergo a systematic study was permutation groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Given any set *X* and a collection *G* of bijections of *X* into itself (known as *permutations*) that is closed under compositions and inverses, *G* is a group acting on *X*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] If *X* consists of *n* elements and *G* consists of *all* permutations, *G* is the symmetric group S*n*; in general, any permutation group *G* is a subgroup of the symmetric group of *X*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] An early construction due to Cayley exhibited any group as a permutation group, acting on itself (*X* = *G*) by means of the left regular representation.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In many cases, the structure of a permutation group can be studied using the properties of its action on the corresponding set.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] For example, in this way one proves that for *n* ≥ 5, the alternating group A*n* is simple, i.e. does not admit any proper normal subgroups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] This fact plays a key role in the impossibility of solving a general algebraic equation of degree *n* ≥ 5 in radicals.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The next important class of groups is given by *matrix groups*, or linear groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Here, *G* is a set consisting of invertible matrices of given order *n* over a field *K* that is closed under the products and inverses.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Such a group acts on the *n*-dimensional vector space *K**n* by linear transformations.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] This action makes matrix groups conceptually similar to permutation groups, and the geometry of the action may be usefully exploited to establish properties of the group *G*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Permutation groups and matrix groups are special cases of transformation groups: groups that act on a certain space *X* preserving its inherent structure.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In the case of permutation groups, *X* is a set; for matrix groups, *X* is a vector space.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The concept of a transformation group is closely related with the concept of a symmetry group: transformation groups frequently consist of *all* transformations that preserve a certain structure.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The theory of transformation groups forms a bridge connecting group theory with differential geometry.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] A long line of research, originating with Lie and Klein, considers group actions on manifolds by homeomorphisms or diffeomorphisms.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The groups themselves may be discrete or continuous.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Most groups considered in the first stage of the development of group theory were "concrete", having been realized through numbers, permutations, or matrices.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] It was not until the late nineteenth century that the idea of an **abstract group** began to take hold, where "abstract" means that the nature of the elements are ignored in such a way that two isomorphic groups are considered as the same group.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] A significant source of abstract groups is given by the construction of a *factor group*, or quotient group, *G*/*H*, of a group *G* by a normal subgroup *H*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Class groups of algebraic number fields were among the earliest examples of factor groups, of much interest in number theory.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] If a group *G* is a permutation group on a set *X*, the factor group *G*/*H* is no longer acting on *X*; but the idea of an abstract group permits one not to worry about this discrepancy.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Rather than exploring properties of an individual group, one seeks to establish results that apply to a whole class of groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The new paradigm was of paramount importance for the development of mathematics: it foreshadowed the creation of abstract algebra in the works of Hilbert, Emil Artin, Emmy Noether, and mathematicians of their school.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] An important elaboration of the concept of a group occurs if *G* is endowed with additional structure, notably, of a topological space, differentiable manifold, or algebraic variety.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] If the multiplication and inversion of the group are compatible with this structure, that is, they are continuous, smooth or regular (in the sense of algebraic geometry) maps, then *G* is a topological group, a Lie group, or an algebraic group.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The presence of extra structure relates these types of groups with other mathematical disciplines and means that more tools are available in their study.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Topological groups form a natural domain for abstract harmonic analysis, whereas Lie groups (frequently realized as transformation groups) are the mainstays of differential geometry and unitary representation theory.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Certain classification questions that cannot be solved in general can be approached and resolved for special subclasses of groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Thus, compact connected Lie groups have been completely classified.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] There is a fruitful relation between infinite abstract groups and topological groups: whenever a group *Γ* can be realized as a lattice in a topological group *G*, the geometry and analysis pertaining to *G* yield important results about *Γ*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] During the twentieth century, mathematicians investigated some aspects of the theory of finite groups in great depth, especially the local theory of finite groups and the theory of solvable and nilpotent groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] As a consequence, the complete classification of finite simple groups was achieved, meaning that all those simple groups from which all finite groups can be built are now known.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] During the second half of the twentieth century, mathematicians such as Chevalley and Steinberg also increased our understanding of finite analogs of classical groups, and other related groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] One such family of groups is the family of general linear groups over finite fields.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Finite groups often occur when considering symmetry of mathematical or physical objects, when those objects admit just a finite number of structure-preserving transformations.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The theory of Lie groups, which may be viewed as dealing with "continuous symmetry", is strongly influenced by the associated Weyl groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] These are finite groups generated by reflections which act on a finite-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The properties of finite groups can thus play a role in subjects such as theoretical physics and chemistry.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Saying that a group *G* *acts* on a set *X* means that every element of *G* defines a bijective map on the set *X* in a way compatible with the group structure.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] where GL(*V*) consists of the invertible linear transformations of *V*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In other words, to every group element *g* is assigned an automorphism *ρ*(*g*) such that *ρ*(*g*) ∘ *ρ*(*h*) = *ρ*(*gh*) for any *h* in *G*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] This definition can be understood in two directions, both of which give rise to whole new domains of mathematics.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] On the one hand, it may yield new information about the group *G*: often, the group operation in *G* is abstractly given, but via *ρ*, it corresponds to the multiplication of matrices, which is very explicit.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] On the other hand, given a well-understood group acting on a complicated object, this simplifies the study of the object in question.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] For example, if *G* is finite, it is known that *V* above decomposes into irreducible parts (see Maschke's theorem).
[src:group-theory/group-theory] These parts, in turn, are much more easily manageable than the whole *V* (via Schur's lemma).
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Given a group *G*, representation theory then asks what representations of *G* exist.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] There are several settings, and the employed methods and obtained results are rather different in every case: representation theory of finite groups and representations of Lie groups are two main subdomains of the theory.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The totality of representations is governed by the group's characters.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] For example, Fourier polynomials can be interpreted as the characters of U(1), the group of complex numbers of absolute value *1*, acting on the *L*2-space of periodic functions.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] A Lie group is a group that is also a differentiable manifold, with the property that the group operations are compatible with the smooth structure.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Lie groups are named after Sophus Lie, who laid the foundations of the theory of continuous transformation groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The term *groupes de Lie* first appeared in French in 1893 in the thesis of Lie's student Arthur Tresse, page 3.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Lie groups represent the best-developed theory of continuous symmetry of mathematical objects and structures, which makes them indispensable tools for many parts of contemporary mathematics, as well as for modern theoretical physics.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] They provide a natural framework for analysing the continuous symmetries of differential equations (differential Galois theory), in much the same way as permutation groups are used in Galois theory for analysing the discrete symmetries of algebraic equations.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] An extension of Galois theory to the case of continuous symmetry groups was one of Lie's principal motivations.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Groups can be described in different ways.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Finite groups can be described by writing down the group table consisting of all possible multiplications *g* • *h*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] A more compact way of defining a group is by *generators and relations*, also called the *presentation* of a group.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Given any set *F* of generators $\{g_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ , the free group generated by *F* surjects onto the group *G*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The kernel of this map is called the subgroup of relations, generated by some subset *D*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The presentation is usually denoted by $\langle F\mid D\rangle .$ For example, the group presentation $\langle a,b\mid aba^{-1}b^{-1}\rangle$ describes a group which is isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z} \times \mathbb {Z} .$ A string consisting of generator symbols and their inverses is called a *word*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Combinatorial group theory studies groups from the perspective of generators and relations.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] It is particularly useful where finiteness assumptions are satisfied, for example finitely generated groups, or finitely presented groups (i.e. in addition the relations are finite).
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The area makes use of the connection of graphs via their fundamental groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] A fundamental theorem of this area is that every subgroup of a free group is free.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] There are several natural questions arising from giving a group by its presentation.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The *word problem* asks whether two words are effectively the same group element.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] By relating the problem to Turing machines, one can show that there is in general no algorithm solving this task.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Another, generally harder, algorithmically insoluble problem is the group isomorphism problem, which asks whether two groups given by different presentations are actually isomorphic.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] For example, the group with presentation $\langle x,y\mid xyxyx=e\rangle ,$ is isomorphic to the additive group **Z** of integers, although this may not be immediately apparent.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Geometric group theory attacks these problems from a geometric viewpoint, either by viewing groups as geometric objects, or by finding suitable geometric objects a group acts on.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The first idea is made precise by means of the Cayley graph, whose vertices correspond to group elements and edges correspond to right multiplication in the group.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Given two elements, one constructs the word metric given by the length of the minimal path between the elements.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] A theorem of Milnor and Svarc then says that given a group *G* acting in a reasonable manner on a metric space *X*, for example a compact manifold, then *G* is quasi-isometric (i.e. looks similar from a distance) to the space *X*.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Given a structured object *X* of any sort, a symmetry is a mapping of the object onto itself which preserves the structure.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The axioms of a group formalize the essential aspects of symmetry.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Symmetries form a group: they are closed because if you take a symmetry of an object, and then apply another symmetry, the result will still be a symmetry.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The identity keeping the object fixed is always a symmetry of an object.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Existence of inverses is guaranteed by undoing the symmetry and the associativity comes from the fact that symmetries are functions on a space, and composition of functions is associative.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Frucht's theorem says that every group is the symmetry group of some graph.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] So every abstract group is actually the symmetries of some explicit object.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The saying of "preserving the structure" of an object can be made precise by working in a category.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Maps preserving the structure are then the morphisms, and the symmetry group is the automorphism group of the object in question.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Almost all structures in abstract algebra are special cases of groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Rings, for example, can be viewed as abelian groups (corresponding to addition) together with a second operation (corresponding to multiplication).
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Therefore, group theoretic arguments underlie large parts of the theory of those entities.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Galois theory uses groups to describe the symmetries of the roots of a polynomial (or more precisely the automorphisms of the algebras generated by these roots).
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The fundamental theorem of Galois theory provides a link between algebraic field extensions and group theory.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] It gives an effective criterion for the solvability of polynomial equations in terms of the solvability of the corresponding Galois group.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] For example, *S*5, the symmetric group in 5 elements, is not solvable which implies that the general quintic equation cannot be solved by radicals in the way equations of lower degree can.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The theory, being one of the historical roots of group theory, is still fruitfully applied to yield new results in areas such as class field theory.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Algebraic topology is another domain which prominently associates groups to the objects the theory is interested in.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] There, groups are used to describe certain invariants of topological spaces.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] They are called "invariants" because they are defined in such a way that they do not change if the space is subjected to some deformation.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] For example, the fundamental group "counts" how many paths in the space are essentially different.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The Poincaré conjecture, proved in 2002/2003 by Grigori Perelman, is a prominent application of this idea.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The influence is not unidirectional, though.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] For example, algebraic topology makes use of Eilenberg–MacLane spaces which are spaces with prescribed homotopy groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Similarly algebraic K-theory relies in a way on classifying spaces of groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Finally, the name of the torsion subgroup of an infinite group shows the legacy of topology in group theory.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Algebraic geometry likewise uses group theory in many ways.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Abelian varieties have been introduced above.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The presence of the group operation yields additional information which makes these varieties particularly accessible.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] They also often serve as a test for new conjectures.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] (For example the Hodge conjecture (in certain cases).) The one-dimensional case, namely elliptic curves is studied in particular detail.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] They are both theoretically and practically intriguing.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In another direction, toric varieties are algebraic varieties acted on by a torus.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Toroidal embeddings have recently led to advances in algebraic geometry, in particular resolution of singularities.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Algebraic number theory makes uses of groups for some important applications.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] captures the fact that any integer decomposes in a unique way into primes.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The failure of this statement for more general rings gives rise to class groups and regular primes, which feature in Kummer's treatment of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Analysis on Lie groups and certain other groups is called harmonic analysis.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Haar measures, that is, integrals invariant under the translation in a Lie group, are used for pattern recognition and other image processing techniques.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In combinatorics, the notion of permutation group and the concept of group action are often used to simplify the counting of a set of objects; see in particular Burnside's lemma.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The presence of the 12-periodicity in the circle of fifths yields applications of elementary group theory in musical set theory.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Transformational theory models musical transformations as elements of a mathematical group.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In physics, groups are important because they describe the symmetries which the laws of physics seem to obey.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] According to Noether's theorem, every continuous symmetry of a physical system corresponds to a conservation law of the system.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Physicists are very interested in group representations, especially of Lie groups, since these representations often point the way to the "possible" physical theories.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Examples of the use of groups in physics include the Standard Model, gauge theory, the Lorentz group, and the Poincaré group.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Group theory can be used to resolve the incompleteness of the statistical interpretations of mechanics developed by Willard Gibbs, relating to the summing of an infinite number of probabilities to yield a meaningful solution.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In chemistry and materials science, point groups are used to classify regular polyhedra, and the symmetries of molecules, and space groups to classify crystal structures.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Molecular symmetry is responsible for many physical and spectroscopic properties of compounds and provides relevant information about how chemical reactions occur.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In order to assign a point group for any given molecule, it is necessary to find the set of symmetry operations present on it.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The symmetry operation is an action, such as a rotation around an axis or a reflection through a mirror plane.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In other words, it is an operation that moves the molecule such that it is indistinguishable from the original configuration.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In group theory, the rotation axes and mirror planes are called "symmetry elements".
[src:group-theory/group-theory] These elements can be a point, line or plane with respect to which the symmetry operation is carried out.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The symmetry operations of a molecule determine the specific point group for this molecule.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In chemistry, there are five important symmetry operations.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] They are identity operation (**E**), rotation operation or proper rotation (**C*n***), reflection operation (**σ**), inversion (**i**) and rotation reflection operation or improper rotation (**S*n***).
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The identity operation (**E**) consists of leaving the molecule as it is.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] This is equivalent to any number of full rotations around any axis.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] This is a symmetry of all molecules, whereas the symmetry group of a chiral molecule consists of only the identity operation.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] An identity operation is a characteristic of every molecule even if it has no symmetry.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Rotation around an axis (**C*n***) consists of rotating the molecule around a specific axis by a specific angle.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] It is rotation through the angle 360°/*n*, where *n* is an integer, about a rotation axis.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] For example, if a water molecule rotates 180° around the axis that passes through the oxygen atom and between the hydrogen atoms, it is in the same configuration as it started.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In this case, *n* = 2, since applying it twice produces the identity operation.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In molecules with more than one rotation axis, the Cn axis having the largest value of n is the highest order rotation axis or principal axis.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] For example in boron trifluoride (BF3), the highest order of rotation axis is **C3**, so the principal axis of rotation is **C3**.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In the reflection operation (**σ**) many molecules have mirror planes, although they may not be obvious.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] The reflection operation exchanges left and right, as if each point had moved perpendicularly through the plane to a position exactly as far from the plane as when it started.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] When the plane is perpendicular to the principal axis of rotation, it is called **σ*h*** (horizontal).
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Other planes, which contain the principal axis of rotation, are labeled vertical (**σ*v***) or dihedral (**σ*d***).
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Inversion (i ) is a more complex operation.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Each point moves through the center of the molecule to a position opposite the original position and as far from the central point as where it started.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Many molecules that seem at first glance to have an inversion center do not; for example, methane and other tetrahedral molecules lack inversion symmetry.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] To see this, hold a methane model with two hydrogen atoms in the vertical plane on the right and two hydrogen atoms in the horizontal plane on the left.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Inversion results in two hydrogen atoms in the horizontal plane on the right and two hydrogen atoms in the vertical plane on the left.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Inversion is therefore not a symmetry operation of methane, because the orientation of the molecule following the inversion operation differs from the original orientation.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] And the last operation is improper rotation or rotation reflection operation (**S*n***) requires rotation of 360°/*n*, followed by reflection through a plane perpendicular to the axis of rotation.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Very large groups of prime order constructed in elliptic curve cryptography serve for public-key cryptography.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Cryptographical methods of this kind benefit from the flexibility of the geometric objects, hence their group structures, together with the complicated structure of these groups, which make the discrete logarithm very hard to calculate.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] One of the earliest encryption protocols, Caesar's cipher, may also be interpreted as a (very easy) group operation.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] Most cryptographic schemes use groups in some way.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] In particular Diffie–Hellman key exchange uses finite cyclic groups.
[src:group-theory/group-theory] So the term group-based cryptography refers mostly to cryptographic protocols that use infinite non-abelian groups such as a braid group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In mathematics, a **Lie group** (pronounced /liː/ *Lee*) is a group that is also a differentiable manifold, such that group multiplication and taking inverses are both differentiable.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Combining these two ideas, one obtains a continuous group where multiplying points and their inverses is continuous.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] If the multiplication and taking of inverses are smooth (differentiable) as well, one obtains a Lie group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups provide a natural model for the concept of continuous symmetry, a celebrated example of which is the circle group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Rotating a circle is an example of a continuous symmetry.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] For any rotation of the circle, there exists the same symmetry, and concatenation of such rotations makes them into the circle group, an archetypal example of a Lie group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups are widely used in many parts of modern mathematics and physics.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups were first found by studying matrix subgroups G contained in ${\text{GL}}_{n}(\mathbb {R} )$ or ⁠ ${\text{GL}}_{n}(\mathbb {C} )$ ⁠, the groups of $n\times n$ invertible matrices over $\mathbb {R}$ or ⁠ $\mathbb {C}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] These are now called the classical groups, as the concept has been extended far beyond these origins.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups are named after Norwegian mathematician Sophus Lie (1842–1899), who laid the foundations of the theory of continuous transformation groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie's original motivation for introducing Lie groups was to model the continuous symmetries of differential equations, in much the same way that finite groups are used in Galois theory to model the discrete symmetries of algebraic equations.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Sophus Lie considered the winter of 1873–1874 as the birth date of his theory of continuous groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Thomas Hawkins, however, suggests that it was "Lie's prodigious research activity during the four-year period from the fall of 1869 to the fall of 1873" that led to the theory's creation.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Some of Lie's early ideas were developed in close collaboration with Felix Klein.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie met with Klein every day from October 1869 through 1872: in Berlin from the end of October 1869 to the end of February 1870, and in Paris, Göttingen and Erlangen in the subsequent two years.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie stated that all of the principal results were obtained by 1884.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] But during the 1870s all his papers (except the very first note) were published in Norwegian journals, which impeded recognition of the work throughout the rest of Europe.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In 1884 a young German mathematician, Friedrich Engel, came to work with Lie on a systematic treatise to expose his theory of continuous groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] From this effort resulted the three-volume *Theorie der Transformationsgruppen*, published in 1888, 1890, and 1893.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The term *groupes de Lie* first appeared in French in 1893 in the thesis of Lie's student Arthur Tresse.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie's ideas did not stand in isolation from the rest of mathematics.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In fact, his interest in the geometry of differential equations was first motivated by the work of Carl Gustav Jacobi, on the theory of partial differential equations of first order and on the equations of classical mechanics.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Much of Jacobi's work was published posthumously in the 1860s, generating enormous interest in France and Germany.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie's *idée fixe* was to develop a theory of symmetries of differential equations that would accomplish for them what Évariste Galois had done for algebraic equations: namely, to classify them in terms of group theory.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie and other mathematicians showed that the most important equations for special functions and orthogonal polynomials tend to arise from group theoretical symmetries.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In Lie's early work, the idea was to construct a theory of *continuous groups*, to complement the theory of discrete groups that had developed in the theory of modular forms, in the hands of Felix Klein and Henri Poincaré.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The initial application that Lie had in mind was to the theory of differential equations.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] On the model of Galois theory and polynomial equations, the driving conception was of a theory capable of unifying, by the study of symmetry, the whole area of ordinary differential equations.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] However, the hope that Lie theory would unify the entire field of ordinary differential equations was not fulfilled.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Symmetry methods for ODEs continue to be studied, but do not dominate the subject.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] There is a differential Galois theory, but it was developed by others, such as Picard and Vessiot, and it provides a theory of quadratures, the indefinite integrals required to express solutions.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Additional impetus to consider continuous groups came from ideas of Bernhard Riemann, on the foundations of geometry, and their further development in the hands of Klein.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The work of Killing, later refined and generalized by Élie Cartan, led to classification of semisimple Lie algebras, Cartan's theory of symmetric spaces, and Hermann Weyl's description of representations of compact and semisimple Lie groups using highest weights.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In 1900 David Hilbert challenged Lie theorists with his Fifth Problem presented at the International Congress of Mathematicians in Paris.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The theory of Lie groups was systematically reworked in modern mathematical language in a monograph by Claude Chevalley.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups are smooth differentiable manifolds and as such can be studied using differential calculus, in contrast with the case of more general topological groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] One of the key ideas in the theory of Lie groups is to replace the *global* object, the group, with its *local* or linearized version, which Lie himself called its "infinitesimal group" and which has since become known as its Lie algebra.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups play an enormous role in modern geometry, on several different levels.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Felix Klein argued in his Erlangen program that one can consider various "geometries" by specifying an appropriate transformation group that leaves certain geometric properties invariant.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This idea later led to the notion of a *G*-structure, where *G* is a Lie group of "local" symmetries of a manifold.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups (and their associated Lie algebras) play a major role in modern physics, with the Lie group typically playing the role of a symmetry of a physical system.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Here, the representations of the Lie group (or of its Lie algebra) are especially important.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Representation theory is used extensively in particle physics.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Groups whose representations are of particular importance include the rotation group SO(3) (or its double cover SU(2)), the special unitary group SU(3) and the Poincaré group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] On a "global" level, whenever a Lie group acts on a geometric object, such as a Riemannian or a symplectic manifold, this action provides a measure of rigidity and yields a rich algebraic structure.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The presence of continuous symmetries expressed via a Lie group action on a manifold places strong constraints on its geometry and facilitates analysis on the manifold.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Linear actions of Lie groups are especially important, and are studied in representation theory.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In the 1940s–1950s, Ellis Kolchin, Armand Borel, and Claude Chevalley realised that many foundational results concerning Lie groups can be developed completely algebraically, giving rise to the theory of algebraic groups defined over an arbitrary field.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This insight opened new possibilities in pure algebra, by providing a uniform construction for most finite simple groups, as well as in algebraic geometry.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The theory of automorphic forms, an important branch of modern number theory, deals extensively with analogues of Lie groups over adele rings; *p*-adic Lie groups play an important role, via their connections with Galois representations in number theory.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] A **real Lie group** is a group that is also a finite-dimensional real smooth manifold, in which the group operations of multiplication and inversion are smooth maps.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] means that $\mu$ is a smooth mapping of the product manifold $G\times G$ into G .
[src:group-theory/lie-group] be a smooth mapping of the product manifold into G .
[src:group-theory/lie-group] We now present an example of a group with an uncountable number of elements that is not a Lie group under a certain topology.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] with $a\in \mathbb {R} \setminus \mathbb {Q}$ a *fixed* irrational number, is a subgroup of the torus $\mathbb {T} ^{2}$ that is not a Lie group when given the subspace topology.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] If we take any small neighborhood U of a point h in ⁠ H ⁠, for example, the portion of H in U is disconnected.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The group H winds repeatedly around the torus without ever reaching a previous point of the spiral and thus forms a dense subgroup of ⁠ $\mathbb {T} ^{2}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The group H can, however, be given a different topology, in which the distance between two points $h_{1},h_{2}\in H$ is defined as the length of the shortest path *in the group* H joining $h_{1}$ to ⁠ $h_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In this topology, H is identified homeomorphically with the real line by identifying each element with the number $\theta$ in the definition of ⁠ H ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] With this topology, H is just the group of real numbers under addition and is therefore a Lie group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The group H is an example of a "Lie subgroup" of a Lie group that is not closed.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] See the discussion below of Lie subgroups in the section on basic concepts.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Let $\operatorname {GL} (n,\mathbb {C} )$ denote the group of $n\times n$ invertible matrices with entries in ⁠ $\mathbb {C}$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Restricting attention to matrix Lie groups simplifies the definition of the Lie algebra and the exponential map.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The following are standard examples of matrix Lie groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] All of the preceding examples fall under the heading of the classical groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] A **complex Lie group** is defined in the same way using complex manifolds rather than real ones (example: $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {C} )$ ), and holomorphic maps.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Similarly, using an alternate metric completion of ⁠ $\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠, one can define a ***p*-adic Lie group** over the *p*-adic numbers, a topological group which is also an analytic *p*-adic manifold, such that the group operations are analytic.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In particular, each point has a *p*-adic neighborhood.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Hilbert's fifth problem asked whether replacing differentiable manifolds with topological or analytic ones can yield new examples.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The answer to this question turned out to be negative: in 1952, Gleason, Montgomery and Zippin showed that if *G* is a topological manifold with continuous group operations, then there exists exactly one analytic structure on *G* which turns it into a Lie group (see also Hilbert–Smith conjecture).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] If the underlying manifold is allowed to be infinite-dimensional (for example, a Hilbert manifold), then one arrives at the notion of an infinite-dimensional Lie group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] It is possible to define analogues of many Lie groups over finite fields, and these give most of the examples of finite simple groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The language of category theory provides a concise definition for Lie groups: a Lie group is a group object in the category of smooth manifolds.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This is important, because it allows generalization of the notion of a Lie group to Lie supergroups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This categorical point of view leads also to a different generalization of Lie groups, namely Lie groupoids, which are groupoid objects in the category of smooth manifolds with a further requirement.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] A Lie group can be defined as a (Hausdorff) topological group that, near the identity element, looks like a transformation group, with no reference to differentiable manifolds nor topological manifolds.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Precisely, a *Lie group* is defined as a topological group that (1) is locally isomorphic near the identities to a matrix Lie group, a closed subgroup of $\operatorname {GL} (n,\mathbb {C} )$ and (2) has at most countably many connected components.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Conversely, let G be a topological group that is a Lie group in the above topological sense and choose a matrix Lie group $G'$ that is locally isomorphic to ⁠ G ⁠ around the respective identities.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Then, by a version of the closed subgroup theorem, $G'$ is a real-analytic manifold and then, through the local isomorphism, *G* acquires a structure of a manifold near the identity element.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] One then shows that the group law on *G* can be given by formal power series; so the group operations are real-analytic and G itself is a real-analytic manifold.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The topological definition implies the statement that if two Lie groups are isomorphic as topological groups, then they are isomorphic as Lie groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In fact, it states the general principle that, to a large extent, *the topology of a Lie group* together with the group law determines the geometry of the group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups occur in abundance throughout mathematics and physics.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Matrix groups or algebraic groups are (roughly) groups of matrices (for example, orthogonal and symplectic groups), and these give most of the more common examples of Lie groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The only connected Lie groups with dimension one are the real line $\mathbb {R}$ (with the group operation being addition) and the circle group $S^{1}$ of complex numbers with absolute value one (with the group operation being multiplication).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The $S^{1}$ group is often denoted as ⁠ $\operatorname {U} (1)$ ⁠, the group of $1\times 1$ unitary matrices.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In two dimensions, if we restrict attention to simply connected groups, then they are classified by their Lie algebras.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] There are (up to isomorphism) only two Lie algebras of dimension two.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The associated simply connected Lie groups are $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ (with the group operation being vector addition) and the affine group in dimension one, described in the previous subsection under "first examples".
[src:group-theory/lie-group] To every Lie group we can associate a Lie algebra whose underlying vector space is the tangent space of the Lie group at the identity element and which completely captures the local structure of the group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Informally we can think of elements of the Lie algebra as elements of the group that are "infinitesimally close" to the identity, and the Lie bracket of the Lie algebra is related to the commutator of two such infinitesimal elements.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] If *G* is any group acting smoothly on the manifold *M*, then it acts on the vector fields, and the vector space of vector fields fixed by the group is closed under the Lie bracket and therefore also forms a Lie algebra.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] We apply this construction to the case when the manifold *M* is the underlying space of a Lie group *G*, with *G* acting on *G* = *M* by left translations *Lg*(*h*) = *gh*.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This shows that the space of left invariant vector fields (vector fields satisfying *Lg***Xh* = *Xgh* for every *h* in *G*, where *Lg** denotes the differential of *Lg*) on a Lie group is a Lie algebra under the Lie bracket of vector fields.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Any tangent vector at the identity of a Lie group can be extended to a left invariant vector field by left translating the tangent vector to other points of the manifold.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Specifically, the left invariant extension of an element *v* of the tangent space at the identity is the vector field defined by *v*^*g* = *Lg***v*.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is finite-dimensional and it has the same dimension as the manifold *G*.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The Lie algebra of *G* determines *G* up to "local isomorphism", where two Lie groups are called **locally isomorphic** if they look the same near the identity element.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Problems about Lie groups are often solved by first solving the corresponding problem for the Lie algebras, and the result for groups then usually follows easily.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] For example, simple Lie groups are usually classified by first classifying the corresponding Lie algebras.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] We could also define a Lie algebra structure on *Te* using right invariant vector fields instead of left invariant vector fields.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This leads to the same Lie algebra, because the inverse map on *G* can be used to identify left invariant vector fields with right invariant vector fields, and acts as −1 on the tangent space *Te*.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] on *G* × *G* sends (*e*, *e*) to *e*, so its derivative yields a bilinear operation on *TeG*.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This bilinear operation is actually the zero map, but the second derivative, under the proper identification of tangent spaces, yields an operation that satisfies the axioms of a Lie bracket, and it is equal to twice the one defined through left-invariant vector fields.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] If *G* and *H* are Lie groups, then a Lie group homomorphism *f* : *G* → *H* is a smooth group homomorphism.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In the case of complex Lie groups, such a homomorphism is required to be a holomorphic map.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] However, these requirements are a bit stringent; every continuous homomorphism between real Lie groups turns out to be (real) analytic.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The composition of two Lie homomorphisms is again a homomorphism, and the class of all Lie groups, together with these morphisms, forms a category.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Moreover, every Lie group homomorphism induces a homomorphism between the corresponding Lie algebras.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Let $\phi :G\to H$ be a Lie group homomorphism and let $\phi _{*}$ be its derivative at the identity.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] which turns out to be a Lie algebra homomorphism (meaning that it is a linear map which preserves the Lie bracket).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In the language of category theory, we then have a covariant functor from the category of Lie groups to the category of Lie algebras which sends a Lie group to its Lie algebra and a Lie group homomorphism to its derivative at the identity.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Two Lie groups are called *isomorphic* if there exists a bijective homomorphism between them whose inverse is also a Lie group homomorphism.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Equivalently, it is a diffeomorphism which is also a group homomorphism.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Observe that, by the above, a continuous homomorphism from a Lie group G to a Lie group H is an isomorphism of Lie groups if and only if it is bijective.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Isomorphic Lie groups necessarily have isomorphic Lie algebras; it is then reasonable to ask how isomorphism classes of Lie groups relate to isomorphism classes of Lie algebras.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The first result in this direction is Lie's third theorem, which states that every finite-dimensional, real Lie algebra is the Lie algebra of some (linear) Lie group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] One way to prove Lie's third theorem is to use Ado's theorem, which says every finite-dimensional real Lie algebra is isomorphic to a matrix Lie algebra.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Meanwhile, for every finite-dimensional matrix Lie algebra, there is a linear group (matrix Lie group) with this algebra as its Lie algebra.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] On the other hand, Lie groups with isomorphic Lie algebras need not be isomorphic.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Furthermore, this result remains true even if we assume the groups are connected.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] To put it differently, the *global* structure of a Lie group is not determined by its Lie algebra; for example, if *Z* is any discrete subgroup of the center of *G* then *G* and *G*/*Z* have the same Lie algebra (see the table of Lie groups for examples).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] An example of importance in physics are the groups SU(2) and SO(3).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] These two groups have isomorphic Lie algebras, but the groups themselves are not isomorphic, because SU(2) is simply connected but SO(3) is not.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] On the other hand, if we require that the Lie group be simply connected, then the global structure is determined by its Lie algebra: two simply connected Lie groups with isomorphic Lie algebras are isomorphic.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] A Lie group G is said to be **simply connected** if every loop in G can be shrunk continuously to a point in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie's third theorem says that every finite-dimensional real Lie algebra is the Lie algebra of a Lie group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] It follows from Lie's third theorem and the preceding result that every finite-dimensional real Lie algebra is the Lie algebra of a *unique* simply connected Lie group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] An example of a simply connected group is the special unitary group SU(2), which as a manifold is the 3-sphere.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The rotation group SO(3), on the other hand, is not simply connected.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] (See *Topology of SO(3)*.) The failure of SO(3) to be simply connected is intimately connected to the distinction between integer spin and half-integer spin in quantum mechanics.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Other examples of simply connected Lie groups include the special unitary group SU(n), the spin group (double cover of rotation group) Spin(*n*) for ⁠ $n\geq 3$ ⁠, and the compact symplectic group Sp(n).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Methods for determining whether a Lie group is simply connected or not are discussed in the article on fundamental groups of Lie groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] If G is a closed subgroup of ⁠ $\mathrm {GL} (n;\mathbb {C} )$ ⁠, then the exponential map takes the Lie algebra of G into ⁠ G ⁠; thus, we have an exponential map for all matrix groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Every element of G that is sufficiently close to the identity is the exponential of a matrix in the Lie algebra.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The definition above is easy to use, but it is not defined for Lie groups that are not matrix groups, and it is not clear that the exponential map of a Lie group does not depend on its representation as a matrix group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] We can solve both problems using a more abstract definition of the exponential map that works for all Lie groups, as follows.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] For each vector X in the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ of G (i.e., the tangent space to G at the identity), one proves that there is a unique one-parameter subgroup $c:\mathbb {R} \rightarrow G$ such that ⁠ $c'(0)=X$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The operation on the right hand side is the group multiplication in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This is called the **exponential map**, and it maps the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ into the Lie group ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] It provides a diffeomorphism between a neighborhood of 0 in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ and a neighborhood of e in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Because the exponential map is surjective on some neighbourhood N of ⁠ e ⁠, it is common to call elements of the Lie algebra **infinitesimal generators** of the group ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The subgroup of G generated by N is the identity component of ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] where the omitted terms are known and involve Lie brackets of four or more elements.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In case X and Y commute, this formula reduces to the familiar exponential law ⁠ $\exp(X)\exp(Y)=\exp(X+Y)$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The exponential map relates Lie group homomorphisms.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The exponential map from the Lie algebra to the Lie group is not always onto, even if the group is connected (though it does map onto the Lie group for connected groups that are either compact or nilpotent).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] For example, the exponential map of SL(2, **R**) is not surjective.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Also, the exponential map is neither surjective nor injective for infinite-dimensional (see below) Lie groups modelled on *C*∞ Fréchet space, even from arbitrary small neighborhood of 0 to corresponding neighborhood of 1.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] A **Lie subgroup** H of a Lie group G is a Lie group that is a subset of G and such that the inclusion map from H to G is an injective immersion and group homomorphism.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] According to Cartan's theorem, a closed subgroup of G admits a unique smooth structure which makes it an embedded Lie subgroup of G —i.e. a Lie subgroup such that the inclusion map is a smooth embedding.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Examples of non-closed subgroups are plentiful; for example take G to be a torus of dimension 2 or greater, and let H be a one-parameter subgroup of *irrational slope*, i.e. one that winds around in *G*.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Then there is a Lie group homomorphism $\varphi :\mathbb {R} \to G$ with ⁠ $\mathrm {im} (\varphi )=H$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The closure of H will be a sub-torus in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The exponential map gives a one-to-one correspondence between the connected Lie subgroups of a connected Lie group G and the subalgebras of the Lie algebra of ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Typically, the subgroup corresponding to a subalgebra is not a closed subgroup.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] There is no criterion solely based on the structure of G which determines which subalgebras correspond to closed subgroups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] One important aspect of the study of Lie groups is their representations, that is, the way they can act (linearly) on vector spaces.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In physics, Lie groups often encode the symmetries of a physical system.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The way one makes use of this symmetry to help analyze the system is often through representation theory.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Consider, for example, the time-independent Schrödinger equation in quantum mechanics, ⁠ ${\hat {H}}\psi =E\psi$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Assume the system in question has the rotation group SO(3) as a symmetry, meaning that the Hamiltonian operator ${\hat {H}}$ commutes with the action of SO(3) on the wave function ⁠ $\psi$ ⁠.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] (One important example of such a system is the hydrogen atom, which has a spherically symmetric potential.) This assumption does not necessarily mean that the solutions $\psi$ are rotationally invariant functions.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Rather, it means that the *space* of solutions to ${\hat {H}}\psi =E\psi$ is invariant under rotations (for each fixed value of E ).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This space, therefore, constitutes a representation of SO(3).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] These representations have been classified and the classification leads to a substantial simplification of the problem, essentially converting a three-dimensional partial differential equation to a one-dimensional ordinary differential equation.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The case of a connected compact Lie group *K* (including the just-mentioned case of SO(3)) is particularly tractable.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In that case, every finite-dimensional representation of *K* decomposes as a direct sum of irreducible representations.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The irreducible representations, in turn, were classified by Hermann Weyl.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The classification is in terms of the "highest weight" of the representation.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The classification is closely related to the classification of representations of a semisimple Lie algebra.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] One can also study (in general infinite-dimensional) unitary representations of an arbitrary Lie group (not necessarily compact).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] For example, it is possible to give a relatively simple explicit description of the representations of the group SL(2, **R**) and the representations of the Poincaré group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups may be thought of as smoothly varying families of symmetries.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Examples of symmetries include rotation about an axis.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] What must be understood is the nature of 'small' transformations, for example, rotations through tiny angles, that link nearby transformations.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The mathematical object capturing this structure is called a Lie algebra (Lie himself called them "infinitesimal groups").
[src:group-theory/lie-group] It can be defined because Lie groups are smooth manifolds, so have tangent spaces at each point.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The Lie algebra of any compact Lie group (very roughly: one for which the symmetries form a bounded set) can be decomposed as a direct sum of an abelian Lie algebra and some number of simple ones.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The structure of an abelian Lie algebra is mathematically uninteresting (since the Lie bracket is identically zero); the interest is in the simple summands.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Hence the question arises: what are the simple Lie algebras of compact groups?
[src:group-theory/lie-group] It turns out that they mostly fall into four infinite families, the "classical Lie algebras" A*n*, B*n*, C*n* and D*n*, which have simple descriptions in terms of symmetries of Euclidean space.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] But there are also just five "exceptional Lie algebras" that do not fall into any of these families.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups are classified according to their algebraic properties (simple, semisimple, solvable, nilpotent, abelian), their connectedness (connected or simply connected) and their compactness.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] A first key result is the Levi decomposition, which says that every simply connected Lie group is the semidirect product of a solvable normal subgroup and a semisimple subgroup.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The identity component of any Lie group is an open normal subgroup, and the quotient group is a discrete group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The universal cover of any connected Lie group is a simply connected Lie group, and conversely any connected Lie group is a quotient of a simply connected Lie group by a discrete normal subgroup of the center.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Any Lie group *G* can be decomposed into discrete, simple, and abelian groups in a canonical way as follows.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] /1 is nilpotent, and therefore its ascending central series has all quotients abelian.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] This can be used to reduce some problems about Lie groups (such as finding their unitary representations) to the same problems for connected simple groups and nilpotent and solvable subgroups of smaller dimension.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Lie groups are often defined to be finite-dimensional, but there are many groups that resemble Lie groups, except for being infinite-dimensional.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The simplest way to define infinite-dimensional Lie groups is to model them locally on Banach spaces (as opposed to Euclidean space in the finite-dimensional case), and in this case much of the basic theory is similar to that of finite-dimensional Lie groups.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] However this is inadequate for many applications, because many natural examples of infinite-dimensional Lie groups are not Banach manifolds.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] Instead one needs to define Lie groups modeled on more general locally convex topological vector spaces.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] In this case the relation between the Lie algebra and the Lie group becomes rather subtle, and several results about finite-dimensional Lie groups no longer hold.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] The literature is not entirely uniform in its terminology as to exactly which properties of infinite-dimensional groups qualify the group for the prefix *Lie* in *Lie group*.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] On the Lie algebra side of affairs, things are simpler since the qualifying criteria for the prefix *Lie* in *Lie algebra* are purely algebraic.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] For example, an infinite-dimensional Lie algebra may or may not have a corresponding Lie group.
[src:group-theory/lie-group] That is, there may be a group corresponding to the Lie algebra, but it might not be nice enough to be called a Lie group, or the connection between the group and the Lie algebra might not be nice enough (for example, failure of the exponential map to be onto a neighborhood of the identity).
[src:group-theory/lie-group] It is the "nice enough" that is not universally defined.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] In abstract algebra, the **symmetric group** defined over any set is the group whose elements are all the bijections from the set to itself, and whose group operation is the composition of functions.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] In particular, the finite symmetric group $\mathrm {S} _{n}$ defined over a finite set of n symbols consists of the permutations that can be performed on the n symbols.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Since there are $n!$ ( n factorial) such permutation operations, the order (number of elements) of the symmetric group $\mathrm {S} _{n}$ is $n!$ .
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Although symmetric groups can be defined on infinite sets, this article focuses on the finite symmetric groups: their applications, their elements, their conjugacy classes, a finite presentation, their subgroups, their automorphism groups, and their representation theory.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] For the remainder of this article, "symmetric group" will mean a symmetric group on a finite set.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The symmetric group is important to diverse areas of mathematics such as Galois theory, invariant theory, the representation theory of Lie groups, and combinatorics.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Cayley's theorem states that every group G is isomorphic to a subgroup of the symmetric group on (the underlying set of) G .
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The symmetric group on a finite set X is the group whose elements are all bijective functions from X to X and whose group operation is that of function composition.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] For finite sets, "permutations" and "bijective functions" refer to the same operation, namely rearrangement.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The symmetric group of **degree** n is the symmetric group on the set $X=\{1,2,\ldots ,n\}$ .
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The symmetric group on a set X is denoted in various ways, including $\mathrm {S} _{X}$ , ${\mathfrak {S}}_{X}$ , $\Sigma _{X}$ , $X!$ , and $\operatorname {Sym} (X)$ .
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Symmetric groups on infinite sets behave quite differently from symmetric groups on finite sets, and are discussed in (Scott 1987, Ch.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The symmetric group on a set of n elements has order $n!$ (the factorial of n ).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] It is abelian if and only if n is less than or equal to 2.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] For $n=0$ and $n=1$ (the empty set and the singleton set), the symmetric groups are trivial (they have order $0!=1!=1$ ).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The group S*n* is solvable if and only if $n\leq 4$ .
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The symmetric group on a set of size *n* is the Galois group of the general polynomial of degree *n* and plays an important role in Galois theory.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] In invariant theory, the symmetric group acts on the variables of a multi-variate function, and the functions left invariant are the so-called symmetric functions.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] In the representation theory of Lie groups, the representation theory of the symmetric group plays a fundamental role through the ideas of Schur functors.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] In the theory of Coxeter groups, the symmetric group is the Coxeter group of type A*n* and occurs as the Weyl group of the general linear group.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] In combinatorics, the symmetric groups, their elements (permutations), and their representations provide a rich source of problems involving Young tableaux, plactic monoids, and the Bruhat order.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Subgroups of symmetric groups are called permutation groups and are widely studied because of their importance in understanding group actions, homogeneous spaces, and automorphism groups of graphs, such as the Higman–Sims group and the Higman–Sims graph.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The elements of the symmetric group on a set *X* are the permutations of *X*.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The group operation in a symmetric group is function composition, denoted by the symbol ∘ or by simple juxtaposition.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The composition *f* ∘ *g* of permutations f and g, pronounced "f of g", maps any element x of X to *f*(*g*(*x*)).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] To check that the symmetric group on a set *X* is indeed a group, it is necessary to verify the group axioms of closure, associativity, identity, and inverses.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Function composition is always associative.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The trivial bijection that assigns each element of *X* to itself serves as an identity for the group.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Every bijection has an inverse function that undoes its action, and thus each element of a symmetric group does have an inverse which is a permutation too.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] A **transposition** is a permutation which exchanges two elements and keeps all others fixed; for example (1 3) is a transposition.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Every permutation can be written as a product of transpositions; for instance, the permutation *g* from above can be written as *g* = (1 2)(2 5)(3 4).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Since *g* can be written as a product of an odd number of transpositions, it is then called an odd permutation, whereas *f* is an even permutation.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The representation of a permutation as a product of transpositions is not unique; however, the number of transpositions needed to represent a given permutation is either always even or always odd.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] There are several short proofs of the invariance of this parity of a permutation.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The product of two even permutations is even, the product of two odd permutations is even, and the product of one of each is odd.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] is a group homomorphism ({+1, −1} is a group under multiplication, where +1 is e, the neutral element).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The kernel of this homomorphism, that is, the set of all even permutations, is called the **alternating group** A*n*.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] It is a normal subgroup of S*n*, and for *n* ≥ 2 it has *n*!/2 elements.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The group S*n* is the semidirect product of A*n* and any subgroup generated by a single transposition.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Furthermore, every permutation can be written as a product of *adjacent transpositions*, that is, transpositions of the form (*a* *a*+1).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The sorting algorithm bubble sort is an application of this fact.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The representation of a permutation as a product of adjacent transpositions is also not unique.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] is a cycle of length three, since *h*(1) = 4, *h*(4) = 3 and *h*(3) = 1, leaving 2 and 5 untouched.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] We denote such a cycle by (1 4 3), but it could equally well be written (4 3 1) or (3 1 4) by starting at a different point.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The order of a cycle is equal to its length.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Cycles of length two are transpositions.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Two cycles are *disjoint* if they have disjoint subsets of elements.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Disjoint cycles commute: for example, in S6 there is the equality (4 1 3)(2 5 6) = (2 5 6)(4 1 3).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Every element of S*n* can be written as a product of disjoint cycles; this representation is unique up to the order of the factors, and the freedom present in representing each individual cycle by choosing its starting point.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Cycles admit the following conjugation property with any permutation $\sigma$ , this property is often used to obtain its generators and relations.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Certain elements of the symmetric group of {1, 2, ..., *n*} are of particular interest (these can be generalized to the symmetric group of any finite totally ordered set, but not to that of an unordered set).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] This is the unique maximal element with respect to the Bruhat order and the longest element in the symmetric group with respect to generating set consisting of the adjacent transpositions (*i* *i*+1), 1 ≤ *i* ≤ *n* − 1.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] In S2*n*, the *perfect shuffle* is the permutation that splits the set into 2 piles and interleaves them.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Note that the reverse on *n* elements and perfect shuffle on 2*n* elements have the same sign; these are important to the classification of Clifford algebras, which are 8-periodic.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The conjugacy classes of S*n* correspond to the cycle types of permutations; that is, two elements of S*n* are conjugate in S*n* if and only if they consist of the same number of disjoint cycles of the same lengths.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] A conjugating element of S*n* can be constructed in "two line notation" by placing the "cycle notations" of the two conjugate permutations on top of one another.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Continuing the previous example, $k={\begin{pmatrix}1&2&3&4&5\\1&4&3&2&5\end{pmatrix}},$ which can be written as the product of cycles as (2 4).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Then *C**μ* is a conjugacy class of S*n*, whose elements are said to be of cycle-type $\mu$ .
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The low-degree symmetric groups have simpler and exceptional structure, and often must be treated separately.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] In this case the alternating group agrees with the symmetric group, rather than being an index 2 subgroup, and the sign map is trivial.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] This group consists of exactly two elements: the identity and the permutation swapping the two points.
