[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] There are also a host of other homomorphisms S*m* → S*n* where *m* < *n*.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] For *n* ≥ 5, the alternating group A*n* is simple, and the induced quotient is the sign map: A*n* → S*n* → S2 which is split by taking a transposition of two elements.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Thus S*n* is the semidirect product A*n* ⋊ S2, and has no other proper normal subgroups, as they would intersect A*n* in either the identity (and thus themselves be the identity or a 2-element group, which is not normal), or in A*n* (and thus themselves be A*n* or S*n*).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] S*n* acts on its subgroup A*n* by conjugation, and for *n* ≠ 6, S*n* is the full automorphism group of A*n*: Aut(A*n*) ≅ S*n*.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Conjugation by even elements are inner automorphisms of A*n* while the outer automorphism of A*n* of order 2 corresponds to conjugation by an odd element.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] For *n* = 6, there is an exceptional outer automorphism of A*n* so S*n* is not the full automorphism group of A*n*.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Conversely, for *n* ≠ 6, S*n* has no outer automorphisms, and for *n* ≠ 2 it has no center, so for *n* ≠ 2, 6 it is a complete group, as discussed in automorphism group, below.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] For *n* ≥ 5, S*n* is an almost simple group, as it lies between the simple group A*n* and its group of automorphisms.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] S*n* can be embedded into A*n*+2 by appending the transposition (*n* + 1, *n* + 2) to all odd permutations, while embedding into A*n*+1 is impossible for *n* > 1.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The symmetric group on n letters is generated by the adjacent transpositions $\sigma _{i}=(i,i+1)$ that swap i and *i* + 1.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] where 1 represents the identity permutation.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] This representation endows the symmetric group with the structure of a Coxeter group (and so also a reflection group).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Other possible generating sets include the set of transpositions that swap 1 and i for 2 ≤ *i* ≤ *n*, or more generally any set of transpositions that forms a connected graph, and a set containing any n-cycle and a 2-cycle of adjacent elements in the n-cycle.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] A subgroup of a symmetric group is called a permutation group.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The normal subgroups of the finite symmetric groups are well understood.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] If *n* ≤ 2, S*n* has at most 2 elements, and so has no nontrivial proper subgroups.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The symmetric group on an infinite set does not have a subgroup of index 2, as Vitali (1915) proved that each permutation can be written as a product of three squares.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] (Any squared element must belong to the hypothesized subgroup of index 2, hence so must the product of any number of squares.) However it contains the normal subgroup *S* of permutations that fix all but finitely many elements, which is generated by transpositions.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Those elements of *S* that are products of an even number of transpositions form a subgroup of index 2 in *S*, called the alternating subgroup *A*.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] Since *A* is even a characteristic subgroup of *S*, it is also a normal subgroup of the full symmetric group of the infinite set.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The groups *A* and *S* are the only nontrivial proper normal subgroups of the symmetric group on a countably infinite set.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] This was first proved by Onofri (1929) and independently Schreier–Ulam (1934).
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The maximal subgroups of S*n* fall into three classes: the intransitive, the imprimitive, and the primitive.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The intransitive maximal subgroups are exactly those of the form S*k* × S*n*–*k* for 1 ≤ *k* < *n*/2.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The imprimitive maximal subgroups are exactly those of the form S*k* wr S*n*/*k*, where 2 ≤ *k* ≤ *n*/2 is a proper divisor of *n* and "wr" denotes the wreath product.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The Sylow subgroups of the symmetric groups are important examples of *p*-groups.
[src:group-theory/symmetric-group] The Sylow *p*-subgroups of the symmetric group of degree *p* are just the cyclic subgroups generated by *p*-cycles.
